# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ray-birdwhistell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Kendon was born on 4 April 1934 in London, son of the writer Frank Kendon and Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] At the University of Cambridge, he read Botany, Zoology and Human Physiology, as well as Experimental Psychology for the Natural Sciences.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] At the University of Oxford, he studied Experimental Psychology, focusing on the temporal organization of utterances in conversation, using Eliot Chapple's chronography.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Then he moved to Cornell University to study directly with Chapple on research leading to his D.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] His thesis topic—communication conduct in face-to-face interaction—spelled out the interests he would pursue in subsequent decades.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] He is noted for his study of gesture and sign languages and how these relate to spoken language.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Phil., he accepted a position in the Institute of Experimental Psychology at Oxford, where he worked in a research group with Michael Argyle and E.R.W.F.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] He initially focused on sign systems in Papua New Guinea and Australian Aboriginal sign languages, before developing a general framework for understanding gestures with the same kind of rigorous semiotic analysis as has been previously applied to spoken language.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Important influences on his theoretical understandings included: Erving Goffman, Albert Scheflen, Ray Birdwhistell, and Gregory Bateson.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Becoming aware of Scheflen's work in 1965, while still at Oxford, he managed to meet him in Philadelphia, where he shared his earliest work; as a result, he was first invited to join William S.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Condon's research team at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic in 1966-67, and then to join Scheflen's research team at Bronx State Hospital in 1967.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] He never actually worked with Birdwhistell directly, but they were in contact, and he did work with films made available to him by Birdwhistell.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] In 1976 he took up an appointment in Canberra, Australia at the Department of Anthropology in the Research School of Pacific Studies, Australian National University.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] He undertook filming everyday interaction in Papua New Guinea but also was able to record a sign language in use in the valley where he worked where there was a considerable number of deaf persons.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] His publication of this work, in three articles in 1980, proved to be a pioneering study; no other accounts on sign language from this part of the world were to appear until the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] This work was republished as a monograph together with a new essay written by colleagues bringing the original work up to date.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] After this he undertook a major investigation of the sign languages in use among indigenous Australians - these are sign languages used for ritual reasons or for practical reasons in situations where speech might is impractical or inappropriate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] These are known as alternate sign languages, distinguishing them from primary sign languages developed among deaf people.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Extensive documentation of his research in Australia is available at the library of the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] In 1988, he returned to Philadelphia, teaching for two years at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Kendon then moved to Naples, Italy and undertook fieldwork on the use of gesture in everyday interaction among Neapolitans and also published a translation of a 19th Century book about Neapolitan gesture (by Andrea de Jorio), comparing it to gesturing among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] In 2004 he published an important general book on the phenomena of gesture which drew extensively on his work in Naples as well as his work in New Guinea and Australia, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Since then he has published various articles on gesture and related topics, including discussions of the place of gesture in theories about language origins.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] In 2012, he returned to Cambridge, where he spent the rest of his life, associated with the Division of Biological Anthropology at Cambridge, and an Honorary Professor in Psychology and Language Sciences at University College London.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Kendon received research grants from the National Science Foundation, the Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research, the American Council of Learned Societies, as well as a Guggenheim Fellowship.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] In addition to teaching at Oxford and Penn, he held positions at Cornell University and Connecticut College in the US, as well as the Università degli Studi di Napoli "L'Orientale", the University of Salerno and the University of Calabria in Italy.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Kendon was a founding editor of the journal *GESTURE* (published by John Benjamins of Amsterdam), along with Cornelia Müller, in 2000.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] He was the sole editor from 2010 to April 2017, when he was replaced by Sotaro Kita.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] In his role as editor of *GESTURE* he was an Ex Officio member of the board of the International Society for Gesture Studies, of which he was elected Honorary President in 2006.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] He edited the book series *Gesture Studies* for John Benjamins, with 9 volumes published between 2007 and 2022.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Colleagues prepared a festschrift in 2014, honoring his contribution to the study of gestures and interaction.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/adam-kendon] Kendon married Margaret Rhoads in 1961; they had three children, Gudrun, Benjamin and Angus.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Ayer conducts custom research in an attempt to win the advertising business of Nichols-Shepard Co., a manufacturer of agricultural machinery.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1895 – Harlow Gale of the University of Minnesota mails questionnaires to gather opinions about advertising from the public.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Waldron conducts qualitative research for Mahin’s Advertising Agency.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1910s – 1911 can be considered the year marketing research becomes an industry.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] George Frederick leaves his position as editor of *Printers' Ink* to begin his research company, the Business Bourse with clients such as General Electric and the Texas Co.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Eastman creates the Association of National Advertisers which is now known as the Association of National Advertising Managers.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] The group’s first project is a postcard questionnaire to determine magazine readership.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] The results introduce the concept of duplication of circulation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Eastman starts his own company, the Eastman Research Bureau which boasts clients such as *Cosmopolitan, Christian Herald*, and General Electric.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Daniel Starch tests reader recognition levels of magazine and newspaper advertisements and editorial content.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] George Gallup begins measuring advertising readership.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] George Gallup validates his survey methodology by using the same tools polling voters during public elections.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] This allows him to successfully compare and validate his study's results against the election’s results.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1940s – Post World War II, the U.S. sees a large increase in the number of market research companies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1950s – Market researchers focus on improving methods and measures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] In their search for a single-number statistic to capture the overall performance of the advertising creative, Day-After-Recall (DAR) is created.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1960s – Qualitative focus groups gain in popularity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] In addition, some advertisers call for more rigorous measurement of the in-market effectiveness of advertising in order to provide better accountability for the large amounts being spent on advertising.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] In response, Seymour Smith and Associates, using Advertising Research Foundation data as a jumping-off point, develops the Communicus System, a comprehensive approach to isolating the in-market impact of advertising across media.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1970s – Computers emerge as business tools, allowing researchers to conduct large-scale data manipulations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 175) Multiple studies prove DAR (Recall) scores do not predict sales.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] The measure, persuasion, also known as motivation, is validated as a predictor of sales.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] The measure known as “breakthrough” is re-examined by researchers who make a distinction between the attention-getting power of the creative execution (attention) and how well “branded” the ad is (brand linkage).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Herbert Krugman seeks to measure non-verbal measures biologically by tracking brain wave activities as respondents watch commercials.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] (Krugman) Others experiment with galvanic skin response, voice pitch analysis, and eye-tracking.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1980s – Researchers begin to view commercials as a “structured flow of experience” rather than a single unit to be rated on the whole, creating moment-by-moment systems such as the dial-a-meter.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 1990s – Ameritest Research creates Picture Sorts to provide accurate non-verbal measurements in a moment-by-moment system.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Picture Sorts results are graphed to visually represent commercial viewers' moment-by-moment image recognition (Flow of Attention), positive and negative feelings (Flow of Emotion), and brand values (Flow of Meaning).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Trends in in-market tracking include a greater focus on the multimedia nature of entire advertising campaigns.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] 2000s – Global advertisers seek an integrated marketing research system that will work worldwide so they can compare results across countries.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] For a look at trends predicted for advertising research in the 21st century, see Seven Trends for the Future.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Robert Heath publishes the seminal and controversial monograph “The Hidden Power of Advertising” which challenged the traditional models used in advertising research and shows how most advertising is processed at an emotional level (not a rational level).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] His monograph leads to re-examination of in-market research approaches that compare the behaviors of those who have seen advertising versus those who have not, such as the Communicus System, and the development of brand new pretesting systems such as the OTX AdCEP system.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] There are two types of research, customized and syndicated.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Customized research is conducted for a specific client to address that client’s needs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Only that client has access to the results of the research.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Syndicated research is a single research study conducted by a research company with its results available, for sale, to multiple companies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Pre-market research can be conducted to optimize advertisements for any medium: radio, television, print (magazine, newspaper or direct mail), outdoor billboard (highway, bus, or train), or Internet.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Different methods would be applied to gather the necessary data appropriately.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Post-testing is conducted after the advertising, either a single ad or an entire multimedia campaign has been run in-market.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] The focus is on what the advertising has done for the brand, for example increasing brand awareness, trial, frequency of purchasing.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Pre-testing, also known as copy testing, is a specialized field of marketing research that determines an ad’s effectiveness based on consumer responses, feedback, and behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Pre-testing is conducted before implementing the advertisement to customers.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] A new area of pre-testing driven by the realization that what works on TV does not necessarily translate in other media.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Greater budgets allocated to digital media in particular have driven the need for campaign pre-testing.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] The addition of a media planning tool to this testing approach allows advertisers to test the whole campaign, creative and media, and measures the synergies expected with an integrated campaign.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Post-testing/Tracking studies provide either periodic or continuous in-market research monitoring a brand’s performance, including brand awareness, brand preference, product usage and attitudes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Some post-testing approaches simply track changes over time, while others use various methods to quantify the specific changes produced by advertising—either the campaign as a whole or by the different media utilized.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Beyond survey-based tracking, causal lift methodologies have gained prominence as advertisers seek evidence of actual behavioral change rather than attitudinal shifts.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Because only experiments, not models, can establish causality, holdout-based lift tests are increasingly regarded as the gold standard against which attribution outputs are calibrated.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Where individual-level randomization is impractical—for example, in linear television, out-of-home, or broad digital campaigns—geo experiments offer a causal alternative by randomly assigning non-overlapping geographic regions to treatment or control conditions and comparing aggregate outcomes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Larsen et al. introduce GeoLift, an open-source framework that uses synthetic control methods to construct a counterfactual for treated regions from a weighted combination of control regions, improving precision when the number of available geos is small.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Overall, advertisers use post-testing to plan future advertising campaigns, so the approaches that provide the most detailed information on the accomplishments of the campaign are most valued.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] With the longitudinal approach, it is possible to go beyond brand awareness, and to isolate the campaign's impact on specific behavioral and perceptual dimensions, and to isolate campaign impact by media.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Attribution models allocate conversion credit across ad exposures using observed user paths rather than experimental manipulation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] These include rules-based systems such as last-touch or first-touch, as well as data-driven multi-touch attribution (MTA).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Incrementality experiments are randomized holdout tests that compare outcomes for exposed and unexposed groups.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] They offer a causal alternative to attribution, but research has found that they frequently produce estimates that diverge substantially from attribution-based figures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] A subsequent large-scale replication using 663 Facebook experiments confirmed that non-experimental methods continue to overestimate causal effects even when flexible machine-learning estimators are applied.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Google developed geo experiments, in which non-overlapping geographic regions are randomly assigned to treatment or control conditions, as a practical method for obtaining causal estimates of advertising return on investment at scale without individual-level randomization.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Facebook's Conversion Lift product similarly uses randomized test and control groups to isolate incremental conversions attributable to ads.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Meta has recommended using lift results to calibrate attribution models when the two diverge.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] In advertising research, **attention** is the qualitative measure of an advertisement's effectiveness in arousing interest in a viewer.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Qualitative is a measurement that is based on peoples emotions and opinions of the advertisement.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Focus Group based methodologies can be used to collect qualitative responses which inform a measure of attention to an advertisement in a simulated environment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] One example of this is a "dummy advertising vehicle test," in which a test Television Advertisement is shown with control ads in a controlled environment designed to simulate a commercial break on television.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] The test ad is embedded alongside either directly competitive advertising, or ads from non-competing product categories, depending on the advertiser's preference.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Respondents are asked the question "Which of these ads did you find interesting?" If the test ad is spontaneously mentioned, then that response is counted toward the attention score.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Quantitative techniques such as Eye Tracking are used to measure attention and spontaneous response to marketing messages.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Quantitative measurements are based on data and numbers that are gathered from studies based on how people react to the advertisements .
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Attention data using this methodology can be collected in a variety of simulated environments such as at home or work, as well as across a variety of different screens and devices.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] In addition to measuring attention, this data can be used by advertisers to optimize the design and placement of advertisements.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Advertisers like to make people feel things in order to gain their attention.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/advertising-research] Eye-tracking techniques can be measured by observing the eye movement and pupil dilation when looking at an advertisement.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Affect is important in psychology as well as in communication, mostly when it comes to interpersonal communication and non-verbal communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] In both psychology and communication, there are a multitude of theories that explain affect and its impact on humans and quality of life.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Affect can be taken to indicate an instinctual reaction to stimulation occurring before the typical cognitive processes considered necessary for the formation of a more complex emotion.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Zajonc asserts that this reaction to stimuli is primary for human beings and is the dominant reaction for lower organisms.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Zajonc suggests affective reactions can occur without extensive perceptual and cognitive encoding, and can be made sooner and with greater confidence than cognitive judgments.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Lazarus on the other hand considers affect to be post-cognitive.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] That is, affect is elicited only after a certain amount of cognitive processing of information has been accomplished.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] A divergence from a narrow reinforcement model for emotion allows for other perspectives on how affect influences emotional development.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Thus, temperament, cognitive development, socialization patterns, and the idiosyncrasies of one's family or subculture are mutually interactive in non-linear ways.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] As an example, the temperament of a highly reactive, low self-soothing infant may "disproportionately" affect the process of emotion regulation in the early months of life.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] In relation to perception, a type of non-conscious affect may be separate from the cognitive processing of environmental stimuli.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] A monohierarchy of perception, affect and cognition considers the roles of arousal, attentional tendencies, affective primacy, evolutionary constraints, and covert perception within the sensing and processing of preferences and discrimination.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Emotions are complex chains of events triggered by certain stimuli.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] There is no way to completely describe an emotion by knowing only some of its components.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Verbal reports of feelings are often inaccurate because people may not know exactly what they feel, or they may feel several different emotions at the same time.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] There are also situations that arise in which individuals attempt to hide their feelings, and there are some who believe that public and private events seldom coincide exactly, and that words for feelings are generally more ambiguous than are words for objects or events.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Affective responses, on the other hand, are more basic and may be less problematic in terms of assessment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] (requiring) minimal attention to occur and...
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] (capable of being) activated without intention or awareness" (1989 p.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Arousal is a basic physiological response to the presentation of stimuli.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] When this occurs, a non-conscious affective process takes the form of two control mechanisms; one mobilization, and the other immobilization.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Within the human brain, the amygdala regulates an instinctual reaction initiating this arousal process, either freezing the individual or accelerating mobilization.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] The arousal response is illustrated in studies focused on reward systems that control food-seeking behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Researchers focused on learning processes and modulatory processes that are present while encoding and retrieving goal values.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] When an organism seeks food, the anticipation of reward based on environmental events becomes another influence on food seeking that is separate from the reward of food itself.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Therefore, earning the reward and anticipating the reward are separate processes and both create an excitatory influence of reward-related cues.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Both processes are dissociated at the level of the amygdala and are functionally integrated within larger neural systems.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Mood, like emotion, is an affective state.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] However, an emotion tends to have a clear focus (i.e., a self-evident cause), while mood tends to be more unfocused and diffused.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Mood, according to Batson, Shaw, and Oleson (1992), involves tone and intensity and a structured set of beliefs about general expectations of a future experience of pleasure or pain, or of positive or negative affect in the future.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Unlike instant reactions that produce affect or emotion, and that change with expectations of future pleasure or pain, moods, being diffused and unfocused, and thus harder to cope with, can last for days, weeks, months, or even years.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Moods are hypothetical constructs depicting an individual's emotional state.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Researchers typically infer the existence of moods from a variety of behavioral referents.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Positive affect and negative affect represent independent domains of emotion in the general population, and positive affect is strongly linked to social interaction.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Positive and negative daily events show independent relationships to subjective well-being, and positive affect is strongly linked to social activity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Recent research suggests that "high functional support is related to higher levels of positive affect".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] The exact process through which social support is linked to positive affect remains unclear.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] The process could derive from predictable, regularized social interaction, from leisure activities where the focus is on relaxation and positive mood, or from the enjoyment of shared activities.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Research has indicated many differences in affective displays due to gender.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Gender, as opposed to sex, is one's self-perception of being masculine or feminine (i.e., a male can perceive himself to be more feminine or a female can perceive herself to be more masculine).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] It can also be argued, however, that hormones (typically determined by sex) greatly affect affective displays and mood.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] According to studies done in the late '80s and early '90s, infants within their first year of life are not only able to begin recognizing affect displays but can begin mimicking the displays and also begin developing empathy.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] A study in 2011 followed up on these earlier studies by testing fifteen 6-12 month old infants' arousal, via pupil dilation, when looking at both positive and negative displays.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Results showed that when presented with negative affect, an infant's pupil will dilate and stay dilated for a longer period of time when compared to neutral affect.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] When presented with positive affect however, the pupil dilation is much larger, but stays dilated for shorter amount of time.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] While this study does not prove an infant's ability to empathize with others, it does show that infants do recognize and acknowledge both positive and negative displays of emotion.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] In the early 2000s over the period of about seven years, a study was done on about 200 children whose mother had "a history of juvenile-onset unipolar depressive disorder" or simply, depression as children themselves.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] In the cases of unipolar depression, a person generally displays more negative affect and less positive affect than a person without depression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Or, they are more likely to show when they are sad or upset, than when they are excited or happy.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] This study that was published in 2010 discovered that the children of mothers that have unipolar depression, had lower levels of positive affect when compared to the control group.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Even as the children grew older, while the negative affect began to stay the same, the children still showed consistently lower positive affect.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] This study suggests that "Reduced PA [positive affect] may be one source of developmental vulnerability to familial depression..." meaning that while having family with depression, increases the risk of children developing depression, reduced positive affect increases the risk of this development.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] But knowing this aspect of depression, might also be able to help prevent the onset of depression in young children well into their adulthood.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] There are some diseases, physical disabilities and mental health disorders that can change the way a person's affect displays are conveyed.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Reduced affect is when a person's emotions cannot be properly conveyed or displayed physically.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] There is no actual change in how intensely they truly feel emotions; there is simply a disparity between emotions felt and how intensely they are conveyed.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] These disorders can greatly affect a person's quality of life, depending on how intense the disability is.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Flat, blunted, and restricted affects refer to a pattern in which an affected person feels an emotion but does not or cannot display it.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] A flat affect is the most severe case in which there is little to no display of emotions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Restricted and blunted affects are less severe.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Disorders involving these reduced affect displays most commonly include schizophrenia, post traumatic stress disorder, depression, autism and traumatic brain injuries.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] One study has shown that people with schizophrenia that experience flat affect can also experience difficulty perceiving the emotions of a healthy individual.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] People who have facial deformities or paralysis may also be physically incapable of displaying emotions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] This is beginning to be corrected though, through "Facial Reanimation Surgery" which is proving not only to successfully improve a patient's affect displays, but also bettering their psychological health.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] There are multiple types of surgeries that can help fix facial paralysis.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Emotions can be displayed in order to elicit desired behaviors from others.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] People have been known to display positive emotions in various settings.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Service workers often engage in emotional labor, a strive to maintain positive emotional expressions despite difficulties in working conditions or rude customers, in order to conform to organizational rules.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Such strategic displays are not always effective, since if they are detected, lower customer satisfaction results.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Perhaps the most notable attempt to feign negative emotion could be seen with Nixon's madman theory.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Nixon's administration attempted to make the leaders of other countries think Nixon was mad, and that his behavior was irrational and volatile.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Fearing an unpredictable American response, leaders of hostile Communist Bloc nations would avoid provoking the United States.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] This diplomatic strategy was not ultimately successful.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] The effectiveness of the strategic display depends on the ability of the expresser to remain undetected.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] It may be a risky strategy since, if detected, the person's original intent could be discovered, undermining the future relationship with the target.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] According to the appraisal theory of emotions, the experience of emotions is preceded by an evaluation of an object of significance to that individual.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] When individuals are seen to display emotions, it serves as a signal to others of an event important to that individual.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] Thus, deliberately altering the emotion display toward an object could be used make the targets of the strategic emotion think and behave in ways that benefit the original expresser.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-display] For example, people attempt to hide their expressions during a poker game in order to avoid giving away information to the other players, i.e., keep a poker face.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] In linguistics, **affect** is an attitude or emotion that a speaker brings to an utterance.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] Lexical choices may frame a speaker's affect, such as *slender* (positive affect) vs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] *scrawny* (negative affect), *thrifty* (positive) vs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] *stingy* (negative) and *freedom fighter* (positive) vs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] In many languages of Europe, augmentative derivations are used to express contempt or other negative attitudes toward the noun being so modified, whereas diminutives may express affection; on the other hand, diminutives are frequently used to belittle or be dismissive.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] For instance, in Spanish, a name ending in diminutive *-ito* (masculine) or *-ita* (feminine) may be a term of endearment, but *señorito* "little mister" for *señor* "mister" may be mocking.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] Polish has a range of augmentative and diminutive forms, which express differences in affect.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] So, from *żaba* "a frog", besides *żabucha* for simply a big frog, there is augmentative *żabsko* to express distaste, *żabisko* if the frog is ugly, *żabula* if it is likeably awkward, etc.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] Affect can also be conveyed by more subtle means.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] Duranti, for example, shows that the use of pronouns in Italian narration indicates that the character referred to is important to the narration but is generally also a mark of a positive speaker attitude toward the character.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] In Japanese and Korean, grammatical affect is conveyed both through honorific, polite, and humble language, which affects both nouns and verbal inflection, and through clause-final particles that express a range of speaker emotions and attitudes toward what is being said.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] ʔaː=tʼo béda=ht̪ow béː=yo-w dá-ːʔ-du-w tʃʰó-w. béda ʔaː qʼlá-w=ʔkʰe.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/affect-linguistics] "(But) I don't want to go away from here.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In definitions commonly used in the social sciences and behavioral sciences, aggression is an action or response by an individual that delivers something unpleasant to another person.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Some definitions include that the individual must intend to harm another person.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In an interdisciplinary perspective, aggression is regarded as "an ensemble of mechanisms formed during the course of evolution in order to assert oneself, relatives, or friends against others, to gain or to defend resources (ultimate causes) by harmful damaging means.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] These mechanisms are often motivated by emotions such as fear, frustration, anger, stress, dominance or pleasure (proximate causes).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Sometimes aggressive behavior serves as a stress relief or a subjective feeling of power." Predatory or defensive behavior between members of different species may not be considered aggression in the same sense.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] There are two subtypes of human aggression: (1) controlled-instrumental subtype (purposeful or goal-oriented); and (2) reactive-impulsive subtype (often elicits uncontrollable actions that are inappropriate or undesirable).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression differs from what is commonly called assertiveness, although the terms are often used interchangeably among laypeople (as in phrases such as "an aggressive salesperson").
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] (1939) proposed that aggression was due to frustration, which was described as an unpleasant emotion resulting from any interference with achieving a rewarding goal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Berkowitz extended this frustration–aggression hypothesis and proposed that it is not so much the frustration as the unpleasant emotion that evokes aggressive tendencies, and that all aversive events produce negative affect and thereby aggressive tendencies, as well as fear tendencies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression can have adaptive benefits or negative effects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggressive behavior is an individual or collective social interaction that is a hostile behavior with the intention of inflicting damage or harm.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Two broad categories of aggression are commonly distinguished.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] One includes affective (emotional) and hostile, reactive, or retaliatory aggression that is a response to provocation, and the other includes instrumental, goal-oriented or predatory, in which aggression is used as a means to achieve a goal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] An example of hostile aggression would be a person who punches someone that insulted him or her.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] An instrumental form of aggression would be armed robbery.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Research on violence from a range of disciplines lend some support to a distinction between affective and predatory aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, some researchers question the usefulness of a hostile versus instrumental distinction in humans, despite its ubiquity in research, because most real-life cases involve mixed motives and interacting causes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A number of classifications and dimensions of aggression have been suggested.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Classification may also encompass aggression-related emotions (e.g., anger) and mental states (e.g., impulsivity, hostility).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression may occur in response to non-social as well as social factors, and can have a close relationship with stress coping style.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression may be displayed in order to intimidate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The operative definition of aggression may be affected by moral or political views.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Examples are the axiomatic moral view called the non-aggression principle and the political rules governing the behavior of one country toward another.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Likewise in competitive sports, or in the workplace, some forms of aggression may be sanctioned and others not (see Workplace aggression).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggressive behaviors are associated with adjustment problems and several psychopathological symptoms such as antisocial personality disorder, borderline personality disorder, and intermittent explosive disorder.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Biological approaches conceptualize aggression as an internal energy released by external stimuli, a product of evolution through natural selection, part of genetics, and a product of hormonal fluctuations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Psychological approaches conceptualize aggression as a destructive instinct, a response to frustration, an affect excited by a negative stimulus, a result of observed learning of society and diversified reinforcement, and a result of variables that affect personal and situational environments.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The term aggression comes from the Latin word *aggressio*, meaning attack.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The Latin was itself a joining of *ad*- and *gradi*-, which meant "step at".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The first known use dates back to 1611, in the sense of an unprovoked attack.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A psychological sense of "hostile or destructive behavior" dates back to a 1912 English translation of Sigmund Freud's writing.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Alfred Adler theorized about an "aggressive drive" in 1908.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Child raising experts began to refer to aggression, rather than anger, from the 1930s.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Ethologists study aggression as it relates to the interaction and evolution of animals in natural settings.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In such settings aggression can involve bodily contact such as biting, hitting or pushing, but most conflicts are settled by threat displays and intimidating thrusts that cause no physical harm.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This form of aggression may include the display of body size, antlers, claws or teeth; stereotyped signals including facial expressions; vocalizations such as bird song; the release of chemicals; and changes in coloration.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The term agonistic behavior is sometimes used to refer to these forms of behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Most ethologists believe that aggression confers biological advantages.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression may help an animal secure territory, including resources such as food and water.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression between males often occurs to secure mating opportunities, and results in selection of the healthier/more vigorous animal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression may also occur for self-protection or to protect offspring.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression between groups of animals may also confer advantage; for example, hostile behavior may force a population of animals into a new territory, where the need to adapt to a new environment may lead to an increase in genetic flexibility.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The most apparent type of interspecific aggression is that observed in the interaction between a predator and its prey.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, according to many researchers, predation is not aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A cat does not hiss or arch its back when pursuing a rat, and the active areas in its hypothalamus resemble those that reflect hunger rather than those that reflect aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, others refer to this behavior as predatory aggression, and point out cases that resemble hostile behavior, such as mouse-killing by rats.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In aggressive mimicry a predator has the appearance of a harmless organism or object attractive to the prey; when the prey approaches, the predator attacks.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] An animal defending against a predator may engage in either "fight or flight" or "tend and befriend" in response to predator attack or threat of attack, depending on its estimate of the predator's strength relative to its own.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Alternative defenses include a range of antipredator adaptations, including alarm signals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] An example of an alarm signal is Nerol, a chemical which is found in the mandibular glands of *Trigona fulviventris* individuals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Release of Nerol by T. fulviventris individuals in the nest has been shown to decrease the number of individuals leaving the nest by fifty percent, as well as increasing aggressive behaviors like biting.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Alarm signals like nerol can also act as attraction signals; in T. fulviventris, individuals that have been captured by a predator may release nerol to attract nest mates, who will proceed to attack or bite the predator.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Also, an individual is more likely to become aggressive if other aggressive group members are nearby.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] One particular phenomenon – the formation of coordinated coalitions that raid neighboring territories to kill conspecifics – has only been documented in two species in the animal kingdom: 'common' chimpanzees and humans.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression between conspecifics in a group typically involves access to resources and breeding opportunities.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] One of its most common functions is to establish a dominance hierarchy.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This occurs in many species by aggressive encounters between contending males when they are first together in a common environment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Usually the more aggressive animals become the more dominant.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In test situations, most of the conspecific aggression ceases about 24 hours after the group of animals is brought together.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression has been defined from this viewpoint as "behavior which is intended to increase the social dominance of the organism relative to the dominance position of other organisms".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Losing confrontations may be called social defeat, and winning or losing is associated with a range of practical and psychological consequences.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Conflicts between animals occur in many contexts, such as between potential mating partners, between parents and offspring, between siblings and between competitors for resources.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Group-living animals may dispute over the direction of travel or the allocation of time to joint activities.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Various factors limit the escalation of aggression, including communicative displays, conventions, and routines.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In addition, following aggressive incidents, various forms of conflict resolution have been observed in mammalian species, particularly in gregarious primates.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] These can mitigate or repair possible adverse consequences, especially for the recipient of aggression who may become vulnerable to attacks by other members of a group.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Conciliatory acts vary by species and may involve specific gestures or simply more proximity and interaction between the individuals involved.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, conflicts over food are rarely followed by post conflict reunions, even though they are the most frequent type in foraging primates.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Other questions that have been considered in the study of primate aggression, including in humans, is how aggression affects the organization of a group, what costs are incurred by aggression, and why some primates avoid aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] For example, bonobo chimpanzee groups are known for low levels of aggression within a partially matriarchal society.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Captive animals including primates may show abnormal levels of social aggression and self-harm that are related to aspects of the physical or social environment; this depends on the species and individual factors such as gender, age and background (e.g., raised wild or captive).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Within ethology, it has long been recognized that there is a relation between aggression, fear, and curiosity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In this approach, when the inconsistency between perception and expectancy is small, learning as a result of curiosity reduces inconsistency by updating expectancy to match perception.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] If the inconsistency is larger, fear or aggressive behavior may be employed to alter the perception in order to make it match expectancy, depending on the size of the inconsistency as well as the specific context.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Uninhibited fear results in fleeing, thereby removing the inconsistent stimulus from the perceptual field and resolving the inconsistency.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In some cases, thwarted escape may trigger aggressive behavior in an attempt to remove the thwarting stimulus.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Like many behaviors, aggression can be examined in terms of its ability to help an animal itself survive and reproduce, or alternatively to risk survival and reproduction.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This cost–benefit analysis can be looked at in terms of evolution.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, there are profound differences in the extent of acceptance of a biological or evolutionary basis for human aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression can involve violence that may be adaptive under certain circumstances in terms of natural selection.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This is most obviously the case in terms of attacking prey to obtain food, or in anti-predatory defense.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] It may also be the case in competition between members of the same species or subgroup, if the average reward (e.g., status, access to resources, protection of self or kin) outweighs average costs (e.g., injury, exclusion from the group, death).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] There are some hypotheses of specific adaptions for violence in humans under certain circumstances, including for homicide, but it is often unclear what behaviors may have been selected for and what may have been a byproduct, as in the case of collective violence.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Although aggressive encounters are ubiquitous in the animal kingdom, with often high stakes, most encounters that involve aggression may be resolved through posturing, or displaying and trial of strength.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Game theory is used to understand how such behaviors might spread by natural selection within a population, and potentially become 'Evolutionary Stable Strategies'.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] An initial model of resolution of conflicts is the hawk-dove game.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Others include the Sequential assessment model and the Energetic war of attrition.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] These try to understand not just one-off encounters but protracted stand-offs, and mainly differ in the criteria by which an individual decides to give up rather than risk loss and harm in physical conflict (such as through estimates of resource holding potential).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Gender plays an important role in human aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] There are multiple theories that seek to explain findings that males and females of the same species can have differing aggressive behaviors.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] One review concluded that male aggression tended to produce pain or physical injury, whereas female aggression tended towards psychological or social harm.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In general, sexual dimorphism can be attributed to greater intraspecific competition in one sex, either between rivals for access to mates and/or to be chosen by mates.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This may stem from the other gender being constrained by providing greater parental investment, in terms of factors such as gamete production, gestation, lactation, or upbringing of young.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Although there is much variation in species, generally the more physically aggressive sex is the male, particularly in mammals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In species where parental care by both sexes is required, there tends to be less of a difference.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] When the female can leave the male to care for the offspring, then females may be the larger and more physically aggressive.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Competitiveness despite parental investment has also been observed in some species.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A related factor is the rate at which males and females are able to mate again after producing offspring, and the basic principles of sexual selection are also influenced by ecological factors affecting the ways or extent to which one sex can compete for the other.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The role of such factors in human evolution is controversial.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The pattern of male and female aggression is argued to be consistent with evolved sexually selected behavioral differences, while alternative or complementary views emphasize conventional social roles stemming from physical evolved differences.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggression in women may have evolved to be, on average, less physically dangerous and more covert or indirect.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, there are critiques of using animal behavior to explain human behavior, especially in the application of evolutionary explanations to contemporary human behavior, including differences between genders.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] According to the 2015 *International Encyclopedia of the Social & Behavioral Sciences*, sex differences in aggression is one of the most robust and oldest findings in psychology.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Past meta-analyses in the encyclopedia found males regardless of age engaged in more physical and verbal aggression while small effect for females engaging in more indirect aggression such as rumor spreading or gossiping.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] It also found males tend to engage in more unprovoked aggression at higher frequency than females.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This analysis also conforms with the *Oxford Handbook of Evolutionary Psychology* which reviewed past analysis which found men to use more verbal and physical aggression with the difference being greater in the physical type.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] There are more recent findings that show that differences in male and female aggression appear at about two years of age, though the differences in aggression are more consistent in middle-aged children and adolescence.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Tremblay, Japel and Pérusse (1999) asserted that physically aggressive behaviors such as kicking, biting and hitting are age-typical expressions of innate and spontaneous reactions to biological drives such as anger, hunger, and affiliation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Girls' relational aggression, meaning non-physical or indirect, tends to increase after age two while physical aggression decreases.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] There was no significant difference in aggression between males and females before two years of age.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A possible explanation for this could be that girls develop language skills more quickly than boys, and therefore have better ways of verbalizing their wants and needs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] According to the journal of *Aggressive Behaviour*, an analysis across 9 countries found boys reported more in the use of physical aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] At the same time no consistent sex differences emerged within relational aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] It has been found that girls are more likely than boys to use reactive aggression and then retract, but boys are more likely to increase rather than to retract their aggression after their first reaction.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Studies show girls' aggressive tactics included gossip, ostracism, breaking confidences, and criticism of a victim's clothing, appearance, or personality, whereas boys engage in aggression that involves a direct physical and/or verbal assault.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This could be due to the fact that girls' frontal lobes develop earlier than boys, allowing them to self-restrain.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] One factor that shows insignificant differences between male and female aggression is in sports.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In sports, the rate of aggression in both contact and non-contact sports is relatively equal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Since the establishment of Title IX, female sports have increased in competitiveness and importance, which could contribute to the evening of aggression and the "need to win" attitude between both genders.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Among sex differences found in adult sports were that females have a higher scale of indirect hostility while men have a higher scale of assault.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Another difference found is that men have up to 20 times higher levels of testosterone than women.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Some studies suggest that romantic involvement in adolescence decreases aggression in males and females, but decreases at a higher rate in females.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Females will seem more desirable to their mate if they fit in with society and females that are aggressive do not usually fit well in society.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Female aggression is not considered the norm in society and going against the norm can sometimes prevent one from getting a mate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, studies have shown that an increasing number of women are getting arrested on domestic violence charges.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In many states, women now account for a quarter to a third of all domestic violence arrests, up from less than 10 percent a decade ago.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The new statistics reflect a reality documented in research: women are perpetrators as well as victims of family violence.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, another equally possible explanation is a case of improved diagnostics: it has become more acceptable for men to report female domestic violence to the authorities while at the same time actual female domestic violence has not increased at all.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This could be the case in a situation where men had become less ashamed of reporting female violence against them⁠‍—‍such a situation could conceivably lead to an increasing number of women being arrested despite the actual number of violent women remaining the same.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In addition, males in competitive sports are often advised by their coaches not to be in intimate relationships based on the premise that they become more docile and less aggressive during an athletic event.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The circumstances in which males and females experience aggression are also different.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A study showed that social anxiety and stress were positively correlated with aggression in males, meaning that as stress and social anxiety increase, so does aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Furthermore, a male with higher social skills has a lower rate of aggressive behavior than a male with lower social skills.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In females, higher rates of aggression were only correlated with higher rates of stress.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Other than biological factors that contribute to aggression, there are physical factors as well.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Regarding sexual dimorphism, humans fall into an intermediate group with moderate sex differences in body size but relatively large testes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This is a typical pattern of primates where several males and females live together in a group and the male faces an intermediate number of challenges from other males compared to exclusive polygyny and monogamy but frequent sperm competition.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Evolutionary psychology and sociobiology have also discussed and produced theories for some specific forms of male aggression such as sociobiological theories of rape and theories regarding the Cinderella effect.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Many researchers focus on the brain to explain aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Numerous circuits within both neocortical and subcortical structures play a central role in controlling aggressive behavior, depending on the species, and the exact role of pathways may vary depending on the type of trigger or intention.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In mammals, the hypothalamus and periaqueductal gray of the midbrain are critical areas, as shown in studies on cats, rats, and monkeys.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] These brain areas control the expression of both behavioral and autonomic components of aggression in these species, including vocalization.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Electrical stimulation of the hypothalamus causes aggressive behavior and the hypothalamus has receptors that help determine aggression levels based on their interactions with serotonin and vasopressin.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In rodents, activation of estrogen receptor-expressing neurons in the ventrolateral portion of the ventromedial hypothalamus (VMHvl) was found to be sufficient to initiate aggression in both males and females.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Midbrain areas involved in aggression have direct connections with both the brainstem nuclei controlling these functions, and with structures such as the amygdala and prefrontal cortex.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Stimulation of the amygdala results in augmented aggressive behavior in hamsters, while lesions of an evolutionarily homologous area in the lizard greatly reduce competitive drive and aggression (Bauman et al.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In rhesus monkeys, neonatal lesions in the amygdala or hippocampus results in reduced expression of social dominance, related to the regulation of aggression and fear.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Several experiments in attack-primed Syrian golden hamsters, for example, support the claim of circuitry within the amygdala being involved in control of aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The role of the amygdala is less clear in primates and appears to depend more on situational context, with lesions leading to increases in either social affiliatory or aggressive responses.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Amygdalotomy, which involves removing or destroying parts of the amygdala, has been performed on people to reduce their violent behaviour.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The broad area of the cortex known as the prefrontal cortex (PFC) is crucial for self-control and inhibition of impulses, including inhibition of aggression and emotions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Reduced activity of the prefrontal cortex, in particular its medial and orbitofrontal portions, has been associated with violent/antisocial aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In addition, reduced response inhibition has been found in violent offenders, compared to non-violent offenders.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The role of the chemicals in the brain, particularly neurotransmitters, in aggression has also been examined.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This varies depending on the pathway, the context and other factors such as gender.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A deficit in serotonin has been theorized to have a primary role in causing impulsivity and aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] At least one epigenetic study supports this supposition.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Nevertheless, low levels of serotonin transmission may explain a vulnerability to impulsiveness, potential aggression, and may have an effect through interactions with other neurochemical systems.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] These include dopamine systems which are generally associated with attention and motivation toward rewards, and operate at various levels.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Norepinephrine, also known as noradrenaline, may influence aggression responses both directly and indirectly through the hormonal system, the sympathetic nervous system or the central nervous system (including the brain).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] It appears to have different effects depending on the type of triggering stimulus, for example social isolation/rank versus shock/chemical agitation which appears not to have a linear relationship with aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Similarly, GABA, although associated with inhibitory functions at many CNS synapses, sometimes shows a positive correlation with aggression, including when potentiated by alcohol.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The hormonal neuropeptides vasopressin and oxytocin play a key role in complex social behaviours in many mammals such as regulating attachment, social recognition, and aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Vasopressin has been implicated in male-typical social behaviors which includes aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Oxytocin may have a particular role in regulating female bonds with offspring and mates, including the use of protective aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Initial studies in humans suggest some similar effects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In human, aggressive behavior has been associated with abnormalities in three principal regulatory systems in the body serotonin systems, catecholamine systems, and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Early androgenization has an organizational effect on the developing brains of both males and females, making more neural circuits that control sexual behavior as well as intermale and interfemale aggression become more sensitive to testosterone.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] There are noticeable sex differences in aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Testosterone is present to a lesser extent in females, who may be more sensitive to its effects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Animal studies have also indicated a link between incidents of aggression and the individual level of circulating testosterone.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, results in relation to primates, particularly humans, are less clear cut and are at best only suggestive of a positive association in some contexts.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In humans, there is a seasonal variation in aggression associated with changes in testosterone.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] For example, in some primate species, such as rhesus monkeys and baboons, females are more likely to engage in fights around the time of ovulation as well as right before menstruation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] If the results were the same in humans as they are in rhesus monkeys and baboons, then the increase in aggressive behaviors during ovulation is explained by the decline in estrogen levels.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This makes normal testosterone levels more effective.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Castrated mice and rats exhibit lower levels of aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Males castrated as neonates exhibit low levels of aggression even when given testosterone throughout their development.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The challenge hypothesis outlines the dynamic relationship between plasma testosterone levels and aggression in mating contexts in many species.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] It proposes that testosterone is linked to aggression when it is beneficial for reproduction, such as in mate guarding and preventing the encroachment of intrasexual rivals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The challenge hypothesis predicts that seasonal patterns in testosterone levels in a species are a function of mating system (monogamy versus polygyny), paternal care, and male-male aggression in seasonal breeders.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This pattern between testosterone and aggression was first observed in seasonally breeding birds, such as the song sparrow, where testosterone levels rise modestly with the onset of the breeding season to support basic reproductive functions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The hypothesis has been subsequently expanded and modified to predict relationships between testosterone and aggression in other species.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] For example, chimpanzees, which are continuous breeders, show significantly raised testosterone levels and aggressive male-male interactions when receptive and fertile females are present.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Currently, no research has specified a relationship between the modified challenge hypothesis and human behavior, or the human nature of concealed ovulation, although some suggest it may apply.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Another line of research has focused on the proximate effects of circulating testosterone on the nervous system, as mediated by local metabolism within the brain.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Testosterone can be metabolized to estradiol by the enzyme aromatase, or to dihydrotestosterone (DHT) by 5α-reductase.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aromatase is highly expressed in regions involved in the regulation of aggressive behavior, such as the amygdala and hypothalamus.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In studies using genetic knockout techniques in inbred mice, male mice that lacked a functional aromatase enzyme displayed a marked reduction in aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Long-term treatment with estradiol partially restored aggressive behavior, suggesting that the neural conversion of circulating testosterone to estradiol and its effect on estrogen receptors influences inter-male aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In addition, two different estrogen receptors, ERα and ERβ, have been identified as having the ability to exert different effects on aggression in mice.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, the effect of estradiol appears to vary depending on the strain of mouse, and in some strains it reduces aggression during long days (16 h of light), while during short days (8 h of light) estradiol rapidly increases aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Another hypothesis is that testosterone influences brain areas that control behavioral reactions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Studies in animal models indicate that aggression is affected by several interconnected cortical and subcortical structures within the so-called social behavior network.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] A study involving lesions and electrical-chemical stimulation in rodents and cats revealed that such a neural network consists of the medial amygdala, medial hypothalamus and periaqueductal grey (PAG), and it positively modulates reactive aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Moreover, a study done in human subjects showed that prefrontal-amygdala connectivity is modulated by endogenous testosterone during social emotional behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In human studies, testosterone-aggression research has also focused on the role of the orbitofrontal cortex (OFC).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This brain area is strongly associated with impulse control and self-regulation systems that integrate emotion, motivation, and cognition to guide context-appropriate behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Patients with localized lesions to the OFC engage in heightened reactive aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Aggressive behavior may be regulated by testosterone via reduced medial OFC engagement following social provocation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] When measuring participants' salivary testosterone, higher levels can predict subsequent aggressive behavioral reactions to unfairness faced during a task.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Moreover, brain scanning with fMRI shows reduced activity in the medial OFC during such reactions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Such findings may suggest that a specific brain region, the OFC, is a key factor in understanding reactive aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Scientists have for a long time been interested in the relationship between testosterone and aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In most species, males are more aggressive than females.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Castration of males usually has a pacifying effect on aggressive behavior in males.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In humans, males engage in crime and especially violent crime more than females.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The involvement in crime usually rises in the early teens to mid teens which happen at the same time as testosterone levels rise.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Research on the relationship between testosterone and aggression is difficult since the only reliable measurement of brain testosterone is by a lumbar puncture which is not done for research purposes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Studies therefore have often instead used more unreliable measurements from blood or saliva.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] No specific response of testosterone levels to competition was observed in female athletes, although a mood difference was noted.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In addition, some experiments have failed to find a relationship between testosterone levels and aggression in humans.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The possible correlation between testosterone and aggression could explain the "roid rage" that can result from anabolic steroid use, although an effect of abnormally high levels of steroids does not prove an effect at physiological levels.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) is the most abundant circulating androgen hormone and can be rapidly metabolized within target tissues into potent androgens and estrogens.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Gonadal steroids generally regulate aggression during the breeding season, but non-gonadal steroids may regulate aggression during the non-breeding season.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Castration of various species in the non-breeding season has no effect on territorial aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In several avian studies, circulating DHEA has been found to be elevated in birds during the non-breeding season.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] These data support the idea that non-breeding birds combine adrenal and/or gonadal DHEA synthesis with neural DHEA metabolism to maintain territorial behavior when gonadal testosterone secretion is low.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Similar results have been found in studies involving different strains of rats, mice, and hamsters.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] DHEA levels also have been studied in humans and may play a role in human aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Circulating DHEAS (its sulfated ester) levels rise during adrenarche (≈7 years of age) while plasma testosterone levels are relatively low.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] This implies that aggression in pre-pubertal children with aggressive conduct disorder might be correlated with plasma DHEAS rather than plasma testosterone, suggesting an important link between DHEAS and human aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Glucocorticoid hormones have an important role in regulating aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In adult rats, acute injections of corticosterone promote aggressive behavior, and acute reduction of corticosterone decreases aggression; however, chronic reduction of corticosterone levels can produce abnormally aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In addition, glucocorticoids affect the development of aggression and the establishment of social hierarchies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Adult mice with low baseline levels of corticosterone are more likely to become dominant than mice with high baseline corticosterone levels.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Glucocorticoids are released by the hypothalamic pituitary adrenal (HPA) axis in response to stress, of which cortisol is the most prominent in humans.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Results in adults suggest that reduced levels of cortisol, linked to lower fear or a reduced stress response, can be associated with more aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, it may be that proactive aggression is associated with low cortisol levels while reactive aggression may be accompanied by elevated levels.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Differences in assessments of cortisol may also explain a diversity of results, particularly in children.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The HPA axis is related to the general fight-or-flight response or acute stress reaction, and the role of catecholamines such as epinephrine, popularly known as adrenaline.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In many animals, aggression can be linked to pheromones released between conspecifics.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In mice, major urinary proteins (Mups) have been demonstrated to promote innate aggressive behavior in males, and can be mediated by neuromodulatory systems.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Mups activate olfactory sensory neurons in the vomeronasal organ (VNO), a subsystem of the nose known to detect pheromones via specific sensory receptors, of mice and rats.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Pheremones have also been identified in fruit flies, detected by neurons in the antenna, that send a message to the brain eliciting aggression; it has been noted that aggression pheremones have not been identified in humans.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In general, differences in a continuous phenotype such as aggression are likely to result from the action of a large number of genes, each of small effect, which interact with each other and the environment through development and life.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In a non-mammalian example of genes related to aggression, the fruitless gene in fruit flies is a critical determinant of certain sexually dimorphic behaviors, and its artificial alteration can result in a reversal of stereotypically male and female patterns of aggression in fighting.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, in what was thought to be a relatively clear case, inherent complexities have been reported in deciphering the connections between interacting genes in an environmental context and a social phenotype involving multiple behavioral and sensory interactions with another organism.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In mice, candidate genes for differentiating aggression between the sexes are the Sry (sex determining region Y) gene, located on the Y chromosome and the Sts (steroid sulfatase) gene.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The Sts gene encodes the steroid sulfatase enzyme, which is pivotal in the regulation of neurosteroid biosynthesis.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] It is expressed in both sexes, is correlated with levels of aggression among male mice, and increases dramatically in females after parturition and during lactation, corresponding to the onset of maternal aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] At least one study has found a possible epigenetic signature (i.e., decreased methylation at a specific CpG site on the promoter region) of the serotonin receptor 5-HT3a that is associated with maternal aggression among human subjects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Mice with experimentally elevated sensitivity to oxidative stress (through inhibition of copper-zinc superoxide dismutase, SOD1 activity) were tested for aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Males completely deficient in SOD1 were found to be more aggressive than both wild-type males and males that express 50% of this antioxidant enzyme.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] They were also faster to attack another male.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The causal connection between SOD1 deficiency and increased aggression is not yet understood.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In humans, there is good evidence that the basic human neural architecture underpinning the potential for flexible aggressive responses is influenced by genes as well as environment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] In terms of variation between individual people, more than 100 twin and adoption studies have been conducted in recent decades examining the genetic basis of aggressive behavior and related constructs such as conduct disorders.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] According to a meta-analysis published in 2002, approximately 40% of variation between individuals is explained by differences in genes, and 60% by differences in environment (mainly non-shared environmental influences rather than those that would be shared by being raised together).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] However, such studies have depended on self-report or observation by others including parents, which complicates interpretation of the results.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The few laboratory-based analyses have not found significant amounts of individual variation in aggression explicable by genetic variation in the human population.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] Furthermore, linkage and association studies that seek to identify specific genes, for example that influence neurotransmitter or hormone levels, have generally resulted in contradictory findings characterized by failed attempts at replication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] The generally unclear picture has been compared to equally difficult findings obtained in regard to other complex behavioral phenotypes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p01] For example, both 7R and 5R, ADHD-linked VNTR alleles of dopamine receptor D4 gene are directly associated with the incidence of proactive aggression in the men with no history of ADHD.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Humans share aspects of aggression with non-human animals, and have specific aspects and complexity related to factors such as genetics, early development, social learning and flexibility, culture and morals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Konrad Lorenz stated in his 1963 classic, *On Aggression,* that human behavior is shaped by four main, survival-seeking animal drives.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Taken together, these drives—hunger, fear, reproduction, and aggression—achieve natural selection.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Wilson elaborated in *On Human Nature* that aggression is, typically, a means of gaining control over resources.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Aggression is, thus, aggravated during times when high population densities generate resource shortages.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] According to Richard Leakey and his colleagues, aggression in humans has also increased by becoming more interested in ownership and by defending his or her property.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] However, UNESCO adopted the Seville Statement of Violence in 1989 that refuted claims, by evolutionary scientists, that genetics by itself was the sole cause of aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Social and cultural aspects may significantly interfere with the distinct expression of aggressiveness.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] For example, a high population density, when associated with a decrease of available resources, might be a significant intervening variable for the occurrence of violent acts.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Culture is one of the factors that influence aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Tribal or band societies existing before or outside of modern states have sometimes been depicted as peaceful "noble savages".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The ǃKung people, for instance, were described as "The Harmless People" in a popular work by Elizabeth Marshall Thomas in 1958.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] However, Lawrence Keeley's 1996 War Before Civilization suggested that regular warfare without modern technology was conducted by most groups throughout human history, including most Native American tribes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Research on hunter-gatherers has revealed a range of behavioral patterns.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] While aggression, conflict and violence can occur, direct confrontation is generally avoided, and disputes are often managed through various verbal and non-verbal social mechanisms.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Different rates of aggression or violence—whether contemporary or historical—have been associated with social structures and environmental factors such as resource distribution or property acquisition, land use, subsistence strategies, and population dynamics.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Gray likens hunter-gatherer bands to social play groups, while stressing that such play is not frivolous or even easy at all times.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] According to Gray, "Social play—that is, play involving more than one player—is necessarily egalitarian.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] It always requires a suspension of aggression and dominance along with a heightened sensitivity to the needs and desires of the other players".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Joan Durrant of the University of Manitoba reports that multiple studies have found an association between physical punishment and higher levels of aggression directed toward parents, siblings, peers, and spouses, even when controlling for other influencing factors.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Similarly, Elizabeth Gershoff of the University of Texas at Austin has found that the more frequently children experience physical punishment, the more likely they are, as adults, to engage in violent behavior toward family members, including intimate partners.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] In countries where the physical punishment of children is more culturally accepted, its association with increased aggression tends to be weaker.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] However, research indicates that physical punishment predicts some increase in child aggression regardless of cultural context.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Although these associations do not establish causality, a number of longitudinal studies suggest that experiencing physical punishment can have a direct causal impact on later aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Similar findings were reported in a 2010 study led by Catherine Taylor at Tulane University, which identified a link between maternal spanking of three-year-old children and an increased risk of later aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Straus contends that such evidence has often been overlooked, largely due to a prevailing belief that spanking is more effective than nonviolent forms of discipline.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] He warns, however, that this belief persists despite evidence of harmful side effects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Cultural and political interpretations of aggression are further complicated by the subjective use of the term "aggressive", which may reflect value judgments depending on the observer's cultural or ideological standpoint.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Whether a coercive or violent act is viewed as aggression—or as legitimate or illegitimate aggression—often depends on the social positions of those involved relative to their culture's structure.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Cross-cultural research has found differences in attitudes towards aggression in different cultures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Within American culture, men from the southern United States were found in a study of university students to react more strongly and respond more aggressively than their northern counterparts when randomly insulted after being bumped into.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Other cultural frameworks frequently considered in aggression research include contrasts between individualistic and collectivist orientations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] These may influence how individuals respond to disputes—for example, through open competition or by accommodating others and avoiding conflict.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] In a study including 62 countries, school principals reported higher levels of aggressive student behavior in cultures characterized as more individualistic and, correspondingly, less collectivist.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Other cross-cultural comparisons related to aggression and conflict have examined differences between democratic and authoritarian political systems, as well as between egalitarian and stratified societies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The economic system known as capitalism has been interpreted by some scholars as relying on human competitiveness and aggression to drive the pursuit of resources and trade.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] This perspective has been viewed both positively, as a motivator for innovation and efficiency, and negatively, as a source of inequality and conflict.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Finally, the perceived legitimacy of aggressive acts are influenced by cultural and political attitudes regarding the social acceptability of certain actions or targets.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] These perceptions are often contested, particularly in cases involving religion or international disputes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] One prominent example is the Arab–Israeli conflict, where acts labeled as aggression by one group may be framed as defense or resistance by another.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Some researchers argue that behaviors such as aggression may be partially learned through observation and imitation of others, a concept rooted in social learning theory.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] This perspective includes the view that exposure to media violence may exert small effects on aggressive behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] However, this remains a subject of ongoing debate, and other scholars have challenged the strength or consistency of such effects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] For example, a prospective study of adolescents found no long-term relationship between violent video game use and subsequent youth violence or bullying.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] A meta-analysis concluded that the effect of violent video games on aggression is generally smaller than that found in studies on television violence.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The magnitude of this effect was positively associated with the intensity of violent content and negatively associated with the amount of time spent playing.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The study concluded that the available evidence was insufficient to establish a causal relationship between violent video games and increased aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Conversely, other research has reported associations between violent video game exposure and heightened aggressive thoughts, feelings, and behaviors both in laboratory settings and real-life contexts.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The frequency of physical aggression in humans peaks at around 2–3 years of age.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] These observations suggest that physical aggression is not only a learned behavior but that development provides opportunities for the learning and biological development of self-regulation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] However, a small subset of children fail to acquire all the necessary self-regulatory abilities and tend to show atypical levels of physical aggression across development.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] They may be at risk for later violent behavior or, conversely, a lack of aggression that may be considered necessary within society.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] However, some findings suggest that early aggression does not necessarily lead to aggression later on, although the course through early childhood is an important predictor of outcomes in middle childhood.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] In addition, physical aggression that continues is likely occurring in the context of family adversity, including socioeconomic factors.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Moreover, 'opposition' and 'status violations' in childhood appear to be more strongly linked to social problems in adulthood than simply aggressive antisocial behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Social learning through interactions in early childhood has been seen as a building block for levels of aggression which play a crucial role in the development of peer relationships in middle childhood.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Overall, an interplay of biological, social and environmental factors can be considered.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Some research indicates that changes in the weather can increase the likelihood of children exhibiting deviant behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The Bobo doll experiment was conducted by Albert Bandura in 1961.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] In this work, Bandura found that children exposed to an aggressive adult model acted more aggressively than those who were exposed to a nonaggressive adult model.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] This experiment suggests that anyone who comes in contact with and interacts with children can affect the way they react and handle situations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Gender is a factor that plays a role in both human and animal aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Males are historically believed to be generally more physically aggressive than females from an early age, and men commit the vast majority of murders (Buss 2005).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] This is one of the most robust and reliable behavioral sex differences, and it has been found across many different age groups and cultures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] However, some empirical studies have found the discrepancy in male and female aggression to be more pronounced in childhood and the gender difference in adults to be modest when studied in an experimental context.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Still, there is evidence that males are quicker to aggression (Frey et al.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] 2003) and more likely than females to express their aggression physically.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] When considering indirect forms of non-violent aggression, such as relational aggression and social rejection, some scientists argue that females can be quite aggressive, although female aggression is rarely expressed physically.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] An exception is intimate partner violence that occurs among couples who are engaged, married, or in some other form of intimate relationship.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Although females are less likely than males to initiate physical violence, they can express aggression by using a variety of non-physical means.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Exactly which method women use to express aggression is something that varies from culture to culture.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] On Bellona Island, a culture based on male dominance and physical violence, women tend to get into conflicts with other women more frequently than with men.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] When in conflict with males, instead of using physical means, they make up songs mocking the man, which spread across the island and humiliate him.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] If a woman wanted to kill a man, she would either convince her male relatives to kill him or hire an assassin.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Although these two methods involve physical violence, both are forms of indirect aggression, since the aggressor herself avoids getting directly involved or putting herself in immediate physical danger.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] See also the sections on testosterone and evolutionary explanations for gender differences above.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] There has been some links between those prone to violence and their alcohol use.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Those who are prone to violence and use alcohol are more likely to carry out violent acts.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Alcohol impairs judgment, making people much less cautious than they usually are (MacDonald et al.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] It also disrupts the way information is processed (Bushman 1993, 1997; Bushman & Cooper 1990).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Recent research further demonstrates that in everyday situations, violations of social norms can be perceived as provocations that trigger aggression, which can have negative consequences for individuals and social coexistence.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Based on the General Aggression Model (GAM), experimental evidence shows that physical provocation affects the internal state (cognition, arousal, and affect) of the provoked person and shapes their responses.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The social status of the provocateur can play a moderating role in this process: a higher-status provocateur induces a more aggression-prone internal state, but the likelihood of verbal retaliation is less affected by internal state when provocation comes from high status.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] These dynamics, illustrate how intentional provocation reduces the probability of ignoring the incident and increases the likelihood of verbal or physical aggression, mediated by changes in the internal state.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Overall, this mechanism highlights the importance of situational and social factors—such as status—in everyday aggression and its regulation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] This also adds to the currently inconclusive evidence about the role of the social status on aggression and highlights to importance of further inquiry.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Pain and discomfort also increase aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Even the simple act of placing one's hands in hot water can cause an aggressive response.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Hot temperatures have been implicated as a factor in a number of studies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] One study completed in the midst of the civil rights movement found that riots were more likely on hotter days than cooler ones (Carlsmith & Anderson 1979).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Students were found to be more aggressive and irritable after taking a test in a hot classroom (Anderson et al.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Drivers in cars without air conditioning were also found to be more likely to honk their horns (Kenrick & MacFarlane 1986), which is used as a measure of aggression and has shown links to other factors such as generic symbols of aggression or the visibility of other drivers.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Frustration is another major cause of aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The Frustration aggression theory states that aggression increases if a person feels that he or she is being blocked from achieving a goal (Aronson et al.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] One study found that the closeness to the goal makes a difference.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The study examined people waiting in line and concluded that the 2nd person was more aggressive than the 12th one when someone cut in line (Harris 1974).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Unexpected frustration may be another factor.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] In a separate study to demonstrate how unexpected frustration leads to increased aggression, Kulik & Brown (1979) selected a group of students as volunteers to make calls for charity donations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] One group was told that the people they would call would be generous and the collection would be very successful.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The other group was given no expectations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] The group that expected success was more upset when no one was pledging than the group who did not expect success (everyone actually had horrible success).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] This research suggests that when an expectation does not materialize (successful collections), unexpected frustration arises which increases aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] There is some evidence to suggest that the presence of violent objects such as a gun can trigger aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] In a study done by Leonard Berkowitz and Anthony Le Page (1967), college students were made angry and then left in the presence of a gun or badminton racket.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] They were then led to believe they were delivering electric shocks to another student, as in the Milgram experiment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Those who had been in the presence of the gun administered more shocks.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] It is possible that a violence-related stimulus increases the likelihood of aggressive cognitions by activating the semantic network.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] A new proposal links military experience to anger and aggression, developing aggressive reactions and investigating these effects on those possessing the traits of a serial killer.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] They come back to the civilian world and may still be haunted by flashbacks and nightmares, causing severe stress.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] In addition, it has been claimed that in the rare minority who are claimed to be inclined toward serial killing, violent impulses may be reinforced and refined in war, possibly creating more effective murderers.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Some recent scholarship has questioned traditional psychological conceptualizations of aggression as universally negative.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Most traditional psychological definitions of aggression focus on the harm to the recipient of the aggression, implying this is the intent of the aggressor; however this may not always be the case.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] From this alternate view, although the recipient may or may not be harmed, the perceived intent is to increase the status of the aggressor, not necessarily to harm the recipient.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Such scholars contend that traditional definitions of aggression have no validity because of how challenging it is to study directly.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] From this view, rather than concepts such as assertiveness, aggression, violence and criminal violence existing as distinct constructs, they exist instead along a continuum with moderate levels of aggression being most adaptive.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/aggression-p02] Such scholars do not consider this a trivial difference, noting that many traditional researchers' aggression measurements may measure outcomes lower down in the continuum, at levels which are adaptive, yet they generalize their findings to non-adaptive levels of aggression, thus losing precision.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He devoted much of the latter part of his life to advocating what he called Cultural Equity, which he sought to put on a solid theoretical foundation through to his Cantometrics research (which included a prototype Cantometrics-based educational program, the Global Jukebox).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In the 1970s and 1980s, Lomax advised the Smithsonian Institution's Folklife Festival and produced a series of films about folk music, *American Patchwork*, which aired on PBS in 1991.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In his late 70s, Lomax completed the long-deferred memoir *The Land Where the Blues Began* (1993), linking the birth of the blues to debt peonage, segregation, and forced labor in the American South.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax's greatest legacy is in preserving and publishing recordings of musicians in many folk and blues traditions around the U.S. and Europe.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] "Alan scraped by the whole time, and left with no money," said Don Fleming, director of Lomax's Association for Culture Equity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] "He did it out of the passion he had for it, and found ways to fund projects that were closest to his heart".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax was born in Austin, Texas, in 1915, the third of four children born to Bess Brown and pioneering folklorist and author John A.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Two of his siblings also developed significant careers studying folklore: Bess Lomax Hawes and John Lomax Jr.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The elder Lomax, a former professor of English at Texas A&M University and a noted authority on Texas folklore and cowboy songs, had worked as an administrator, and later Secretary of the Alumni Society, of the University of Texas.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Due to childhood asthma, chronic ear infections, and generally frail health, Lomax was mostly homeschooled in elementary school.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In Dallas, he entered the Terrill School for Boys (a small prep school that later became St.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax excelled at Terrill and then transferred to the Choate School (now Choate Rosemary Hall) in Connecticut for a year, graduating eighth in his class at age 15 in 1930.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Owing to his mother's declining health, however, rather than going to Harvard University as his father had wished, Lomax matriculated at the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] A roommate, future anthropologist Walter Goldschmidt, recalled Lomax as "frighteningly smart, probably classifiable as a genius", though Goldschmidt remembers Lomax exclaiming one night while studying: "Damn it!
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The hardest thing I've had to learn is that I'm not a genius." At the University of Texas, Lomax read Nietzsche and developed an interest in philosophy.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He joined and wrote a few columns for the school paper, *The Daily Texan*, but resigned when it refused to publish an editorial he had written on birth control.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] At this time he also began collecting "race" records and taking his dates to black-owned nightclubs, at the risk of expulsion.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] During the spring term his mother died, and his youngest sister Bess, age 10, was sent to live with an aunt.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Although the Great Depression was rapidly causing his family's resources to decline, Harvard provided enough financial aid for the 16-year-old Lomax to spend his second year there.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He enrolled in philosophy and physics and also pursued a long-distance informal reading course in Plato and the Pre-Socratics with University of Texas professor Albert P.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He also became involved in radical politics and contracted pneumonia.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] His grades suffered, diminishing his financial aid prospects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax, now 17, therefore took a break from studying to join his father's folk song collecting field trips for the Library of Congress, co-authoring *American Ballads and Folk Songs* (1934) and *Negro Folk Songs as Sung by Lead Belly* (1936).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] His first field collecting without his father was done with Zora Neale Hurston and Mary Elizabeth Barnicle in the summer of 1935.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He returned to the University of Texas that fall and was awarded a Bachelor of Arts in philosophy, summa cum laude, and membership in Phi Beta Kappa in May 1936.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lack of money prevented him from immediately attending graduate school at the University of Chicago, as he had intended, but he later corresponded with and pursued graduate studies with Melville J.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Herskovits at Columbia University and with Ray Birdwhistell at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Alan Lomax married Elizabeth Harold Goodman, then a student at the University of Texas, in February 1937.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] They were married for 12 years and had a daughter, Anne (later known as Anna).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Elizabeth assisted him in recording in Haiti, Alabama, Appalachia, and Mississippi.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Elizabeth also wrote radio scripts of folk operas featuring American music that were broadcast over the BBC Home Service as part of the war effort.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] During the 1950s, after she and Lomax divorced, she conducted lengthy interviews for Lomax with folk music figures, including Vera Ward Hall and the Reverend Gary Davis.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] All those who assisted and worked with him were accurately credited on the resultant Library of Congress and other recordings, as well as in his many books, films, and publications.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] From 1937 to 1942, Lomax was Assistant in Charge of the Archive of Folk Song of the Library of Congress to which he and his father and numerous collaborators contributed more than ten thousand field recordings.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] A pioneering oral historian, Lomax recorded substantial interviews with many folk, blues, and jazz musicians, including Woody Guthrie, Lead Belly, Jelly Roll Morton, and Big Bill Broonzy.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] On one of his trips in 1941, he went to Clarksdale, Mississippi, hoping to record the music of Robert Johnson.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] When he arrived, he was told by locals that Johnson had died, but that another local musician, Muddy Waters, might be willing to record his music for Lomax.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Using recording equipment that filled the trunk of his car, Lomax recorded Waters' music; it is said that hearing Lomax's recording was the motivation that Waters needed to leave his farm job in Mississippi to pursue a career as a blues musician full-time, first in Memphis and later in Chicago.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] As part of this work, Lomax traveled through Michigan and Wisconsin in 1938 to record and document the traditional music of that region.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Over four hundred recordings from this collection are now available at the Library of Congress.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] "He traveled in a 1935 Plymouth sedan, toting a Presto instantaneous disc recorder and a movie camera.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] As host, Lomax sang and presented other performers, including Burl Ives, Woody Guthrie, Lead Belly, Pete Seeger, Josh White, and the Golden Gate Quartet.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1940, under Lomax's supervision, RCA made two groundbreaking suites of commercial folk music recordings: Woody Guthrie's *Dust Bowl Ballads* and Lead Belly's *The Midnight Special and Other Southern Prison Songs*.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Though they did not sell especially well when released, Lomax's biographer John Szwed calls these "some of the first concept albums".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1940, Lomax and his close friend Nicholas Ray wrote and produced the 15-minute program *Back Where I Came From*, which aired three nights per week on CBS and featured folk tales, proverbs, prose, and sermons, as well as songs, organized thematically.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Its racially integrated cast included Burl Ives, Lead Belly, Josh White, Sonny Terry, and Brownie McGhee.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Eleanor Roosevelt invited Lomax to Hyde Park.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Despite its success and high visibility, *Back Where I Come From* never picked up a commercial sponsor.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The show ran for only twenty-one weeks before it was suddenly canceled in February 1941.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] On hearing the news, Woody Guthrie wrote Lomax from California, "Too honest again, I suppose?
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] O well, this country's a getting to where it can't hear its own voice.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] A second series of interviews, called "Dear Mr.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] President", was recorded in January and February 1942.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] While serving in the United States Army in World War II, Lomax produced and hosted numerous radio programs in connection with the war effort.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The 1944 "ballad opera", *The Martins and the Coys*, broadcast in Britain (but not the U.S.) by the BBC, featuring Burl Ives, Woody Guthrie, Will Geer, Sonny Terry, Pete Seeger, and Fiddlin' Arthur Smith, among others, was released on Rounder Records in 2000.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In the late 1940s, Lomax produced a series of commercial folk music albums for Decca Records and organized a series of concerts at New York's Town Hall and Carnegie Hall, featuring blues, calypso, and flamenco music.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He also was a key participant in the V.D.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Radio Project in 1949, creating a number of "ballad dramas" featuring country and gospel superstars, including Roy Acuff, Woody Guthrie, Hank Williams, and Sister Rosetta Tharpe (among others), that aimed to convince men and women suffering from syphilis to seek treatment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In December 1949, a newspaper printed a story, "Red Convictions Scare 'Travelers'", that mentioned a dinner given by the Civil Rights Association to honor five lawyers who had defended people accused of being Communists.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The article mentioned Alan Lomax as one of the sponsors of the dinner, along with C.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Wallace in 1948; music critic Olin Downes of *The New York Times*; and W.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Du Bois, all of whom it accused of being members of Communist front groups.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The following June, *Red Channels*, a pamphlet edited by former F.B.I. agents which became the basis for the entertainment industry blacklist of the 1950s, listed Lomax as an artist or broadcast journalist sympathetic to Communism.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He set sail on September 24, 1950, on board the steamer RMS *Mauretania*.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Sure enough, in October, FBI agents were interviewing Lomax's friends and acquaintances.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax never told his family exactly why he went to Europe, only that he was developing a library of world folk music for Columbia.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Nor did he allow anyone to say he was forced to leave.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In a letter to the editor of a British newspaper, Lomax took a writer to task for describing him as a "victim of witch-hunting," insisting that he was in the UK only to work on his Columbia Project.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax spent the 1950s based in London, from where he edited the 18-volume *Columbia World Library of Folk and Primitive Music*, an anthology issued on newly invented LP records.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1953 a young David Attenborough commissioned Lomax to host six 20-minute episodes of the BBC TV series *The Song Hunter*, which featured performances by a wide range of traditional musicians from all over Britain and Ireland, as well as Lomax himself.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1957, Lomax hosted a folk music show on BBC's Home Service titled *A Ballad Hunter* and organized a skiffle group, Alan Lomax and the Ramblers (who included Ewan MacColl, Peggy Seeger, and Shirley Collins), which appeared on British television.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] His ballad opera *Big Rock Candy Mountain* premiered December 1955 at Joan Littlewood's Theatre Workshop and featured Ramblin' Jack Elliot.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In Scotland, Lomax is credited with being an inspiration for the School of Scottish Studies, founded in 1951, the year of his first visit there.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The pair amassed one of the most representative folk song collections of any culture.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] From Lomax's Spanish and Italian recordings emerged one of the first theories explaining the types of folk singing that predominate in particular areas, a theory that incorporates work style, the environment, and the degrees of social and sexual freedom.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The occasion marked the first time rock and roll and bluegrass were performed on the Carnegie Hall Stage.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] "The time has come for Americans not to be ashamed of what we go for, musically, from primitive ballads to rock 'n' roll songs", Lomax told the audience.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] According to Izzy Young, the audience booed when he told them to lay down their prejudices and listen to rock 'n' roll.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Alan Lomax had met 20-year-old English folk singer Shirley Collins while living in London.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The two were romantically involved and lived together for some years.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] When Lomax obtained a contract from Atlantic Records to re-record some of the American musicians first recorded in the 1940s, using improved equipment, Collins accompanied him.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Recordings from this trip were issued under the title *Sounds of the* *South* and some were also featured in the Coen brothers' 2000 film *O Brother, Where Art Thou?*.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax wished to marry Collins but when the recording trip was over, she returned to England and married Austin John Marshall.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In an interview in *The Guardian* newspaper, Collins expressed irritation that *The Land Where The Blues Began*, Lomax's 1993 account of the journey, barely mentioned her.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] "All it said was, 'Shirley Collins was along for the trip'.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] I was part of the recording process, I made notes, I drafted contracts, I was involved in every part".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Collins addressed the perceived omission in her memoir, *America Over the Water*, published in 2004.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax married Antoinette Marchand on August 26, 1961.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] They separated the following year and divorced in 1967.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1962, Lomax and singer and civil rights activist Guy Carawan, music director at the Highlander Folk School in Monteagle, Tennessee, produced the album *Freedom in the Air: Albany Georgia, 1961–62* for the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee on Vanguard Records.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax was a consultant to Carl Sagan for the Voyager Golden Record sent into space on the 1977 Voyager Spacecraft to represent the music of the earth.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Sagan later wrote that it was Lomax "who was a persistent and vigorous advocate for including ethnic music even at the expense of Western classical music.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He brought pieces so compelling and beautiful that we gave in to his suggestions more often than I would have thought possible.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Alan Lomax died in Safety Harbor, Florida, on July 19, 2002, at the age of 87.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] As a member of the Popular Front and People's Songs in the 1940s, Alan Lomax promoted what was then known as "One World" and today is called multiculturalism.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In the late forties he produced a series of concerts at Town Hall and Carnegie Hall that presented flamenco guitar and calypso, along with country blues, Appalachian music, Andean music, and jazz.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] His radio shows of the 1940s and 1950s explored musics of all the world's peoples.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax recognized that folklore (like all forms of creativity) occurs at the local and not the national level and flourishes not in isolation but in fruitful interplay with other cultures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He was dismayed that mass communications appeared to be crushing local cultural expressions and languages.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1950 he echoed anthropologist Bronisław Malinowski (1884–1942), who believed the role of the ethnologist should be that of advocate for primitive man (as indigenous people were then called), when he urged folklorists to similarly advocate for the folk.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Some, such as Richard Dorson, objected that scholars shouldn't act as cultural arbiters, but Lomax believed it was unethical to stand idly by as the magnificent variety of the world's cultures and languages was "grayed out" by centralized commercial entertainment and educational systems.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Although he acknowledged potential problems with intervention, he urged that folklorists with their special training actively assist communities in safeguarding and revitalizing their own local traditions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Similar ideas had been put into practice by Benjamin Botkin, Harold W.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Jones, who believed that folklore studied by folklorists should be returned to its home communities to enable it to thrive anew.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] They have been realized in the annual (since 1967) Smithsonian Folk Festival on the Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1983, Lomax founded The Association for Cultural Equity (ACE).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] It is housed at the Fine Arts Campus of Hunter College in New York City and is the custodian of the Alan Lomax Archive.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The Association's mission is to "facilitate cultural equity" and practice "cultural feedback" and "preserve, publish, repatriate and freely disseminate" its collections.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Though Alan Lomax's appeals to anthropology conferences and repeated letters to UNESCO fell on deaf ears, the modern world seems to have caught up to his vision.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] From 1942 to 1979, Lomax repeatedly was investigated and interviewed by the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), but nothing incriminating was discovered, and the investigation was abandoned.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Scholar and jazz pianist Ted Gioia uncovered and published extracts from Alan Lomax's 800-page FBI files.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The investigation appears to have started when an anonymous informant reported overhearing Lomax's father telling guests in 1941 about what he considered his son's communist sympathies.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Looking for leads, the FBI seized on the fact that, at the age of 17 in 1932 while attending Harvard University for a year, Lomax had been arrested in Boston, Massachusetts in connection with a political demonstration.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax had been charged with disturbing the peace and fined $25.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Berkman, however, had been cleared of all accusations against her and was not deported.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Nor had Lomax's Harvard academic record been affected in any way by his activities in her defense.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Nevertheless, the bureau continued trying vainly to show that in 1932 Lomax had either distributed communist literature or made public speeches in support of the Communist Party.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax left Harvard, after having spent his sophomore year there, to join John A.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax and John Lomax Jr. in collecting folk songs for the Library of Congress and to assist his father in writing his books.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In withdrawing him (in addition to not being able to afford the tuition), the elder Lomax had probably wanted to separate his son from new political associates that he considered undesirable.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] But Alan had also not been happy there and probably also wanted to be nearer his bereaved father and young sister, Bess, and to return to the close friends he had made during his first year at the University of Texas.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In June 1942 the FBI approached the Librarian of Congress, Archibald McLeish, in an attempt to have Lomax fired as Assistant in Charge of the Library's Archive of American Folk Song.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] At the time, Lomax was preparing for a field trip to the Mississippi Delta on behalf of the Library, where he made landmark recordings of Muddy Waters, Son House, and David "Honeyboy" Edwards, among others.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] McLeish wrote to Hoover, defending Lomax: "I have studied the findings of these reports very carefully.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] I do not find positive evidence that Mr.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax, who was a founding member of People's Songs, was in charge of campaign music for Henry A.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Wallace's 1948 Presidential run on the Progressive Party ticket on a platform opposing the arms race and supporting civil rights for Jews and African Americans.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Subsequently, Lomax was one of the performers listed in the publication Red Channels as a possible Communist sympathizer and was consequently blacklisted from working in U.S. entertainment industries.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] A 2007 BBC news article revealed that in the early 1950s, the British MI5 had placed Lomax under surveillance as a suspected Communist.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Its report concluded that although Lomax undoubtedly held "left wing" views, there was no evidence he was a Communist.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The FBI again investigated Lomax in 1956 and sent a 68-page report to the CIA and the Attorney General's office.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] However, William Tompkins, assistant attorney general, wrote to Hoover that the investigation had failed to disclose sufficient evidence to warrant prosecution or the suspension of Lomax's passport.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Then, as late as 1979, an FBI report suggested that Lomax had recently impersonated an FBI agent.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The report appears to have been based on mistaken identity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The person who reported the incident to the FBI said that the man in question was around 43, about 5 feet 9 inches and 190 pounds.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The FBI investigation was concluded the following year, shortly after Lomax's 65th birthday.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Alan Lomax received the National Medal of Arts from President Ronald Reagan in 1986; a Library of Congress Living Legend Award in 2000; and was awarded an Honorary Doctorate in Philosophy from Tulane University in 2001.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] He won the National Book Critics Circle Award and the Ralph J.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Gleason Music Book Award in 1993 for his book *The Land Where the Blues Began*, connecting the story of the origins of blues music with the prevalence of forced labor in the pre-World War II South (especially on the Mississippi levees).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax also received a posthumous Grammy Trustees Award for his lifetime achievements in 2003.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In January 2012, the American Folklife Center at the Library of Congress, with the Association for Cultural Equity, announced that it would release Lomax's vast archive in digital form.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax spent the last 20 years of his life working on an interactive multimedia educational computer project he called the Global Jukebox, which included 5,000 hours of sound recordings, 400,000 feet of film, 3,000 videotapes, and 5,000 photographs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] By February 2012, 17,000 music tracks from his archived collection were expected to be made available for free streaming, and later some of that music may be for sale as CDs or digital downloads.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] As of March 2012 this has been accomplished.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Approximately 17,400 of Lomax's recordings from 1946 and later have been made available free online.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] This is material from Alan Lomax's independent archive, begun in 1946, which has been digitized and offered by the Association for Cultural Equity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] This is "distinct from the thousands of earlier recordings on acetate and aluminum discs he made from 1933 to 1942 under the auspices of the Library of Congress.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] This earlier collection – which includes the famous Jelly Roll Morton, Woody Guthrie, Lead Belly, and Muddy Waters sessions, as well as Lomax's prodigious collections made in Haiti and Eastern Kentucky (1937) – is the provenance of the American Folklife Center" at the Library of Congress.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The Lomax Kentucky Recordings, a collaborative project from the Association for Cultural Equity, Berea College, The Library of Congress, and the University of Kentucky, highlights and contextualizes a subset of documentary sound recordings focused on rural Kentucky music and lore.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In 1999 electronica musician Moby released his fifth album *Play*.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] It extensively used samples from field recordings collected by Lomax on the 1993 box set *Sounds of the South: A Musical Journey from the Georgia Sea Islands to the Mississippi Delta*.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] The album went on to be certified platinum in more than 20 countries.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] In his autobiography *Chronicles, Part One*, Bob Dylan recollects a 1961 scene: "There was an art movie house in the Village on 12th Street that showed foreign movies—French, Italian, German.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/alan-lomax] Lomax is portrayed by actor Norbert Leo Butz in *A Complete Unknown*, the 2024 feature film about Bob Dylan's early career.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] When the information from the sender changes the behavior of a receiver, the information is referred to as a "signal".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Signalling theory predicts that for a signal to be maintained in the population, both the sender and receiver should usually receive some benefit from the interaction.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Signal production by senders and the perception and subsequent response of receivers are thought to coevolve.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Signals often involve multiple mechanisms, e.g., both visual and auditory, and for a signal to be understood, the coordinated behavior of both sender and receiver requires careful study.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The sounds animals make are important because they communicate the animals' state.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some animals species have been taught simple versions of human languages, as for instance the American Sign Language taught to the chimpanzee Washoe.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Animals can use, for example, electrolocation and echolocation to communicate about prey and location.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] of distinctive body parts or bodily movements.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Animals reveal or accentuate a body part to relay certain information.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] displays its bright yellow bill on the ground next over its chick when it has returned to the nest with food.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] by tapping the red spot on the lower mandible of the parent herring gull's bill.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This signal stimulates the parent to regurgitate food and completes the feeding signal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The distinctive morphological feature accentuated in this communication is the parent's red-spotted bill, while the tapping towards the ground makes the red spot visible to the chick, demonstrating a distinctive movement.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] to understand if language was somehow evolved by gestures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] He found that both apes and humans only use intentional gestures to communicate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] in animal communication are facial gestures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] were studied to understand how they reacted to interactions with a familiar animal caretaker.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] frequently during mutual interactions with a caretaker.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] studied facial expression in mice in response to increments of increasing pain.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] He found that mice exhibited five recognizable facial expressions: orbital tightening, nose and cheek bulge, and changes in ear and whisker carriage.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Social animals use gaze-following as a form of communication through monitoring head and eye orientation in other mammals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] A broad range of animals have been proven to exhibit the latter, however, only apes, dogs, wolves, and corvids (ravens) have been able to follow another's gaze into distant space.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] were unable to demonstrate "geometric gaze following".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Researchers do not yet have a clear picture of the cognitive basis of gaze following, but developmental evidence indicates that "simple" gaze following and "geometric" gaze following probably rely on different cognitive mechanisms.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Colour change can be separated into changes that occur during growth and development, and those triggered by mood, social context, or abiotic factors such as temperature.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] ) that can change the apparent colour, opacity, and reflectiveness of their skin.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] , rapid changes in skin colour are used while hunting and in courtship rituals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Cuttlefish may display two entirely different signals simultaneously from opposite sides of their body.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] When a male cuttlefish courts a female in the presence of other males, he displays a male pattern facing the female and a female pattern facing away, to deceive other males.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, when a female olive baboon begins to ovulate, her anogenital area swells and turns a bright red/pink.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This signals to males that she is ready to mate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] and thus capable of communicating visually in dark ocean environments.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] relationship with bioluminescent bacteria.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Animals exhibit bioluminescent light to lure in prey, attract a mate, or protect themselves from potential predators.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There are many different types of signals that animals use to differentiate their position of direction, location, and distance.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Practitioners study the issues of animal position by geometric viewings.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Environmental and social influences are indicators of geometric viewings.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Animals rely on signals called electrolocating and echolocating; they use sensory senses in order to navigate and find prey.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Signals are used as a form of commutation through the environment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Active signals or other types of signals influence receivers behavior and signals move quicker in distance to reach receivers.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Many animals communicate through vocalization.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Vocal communication serves many purposes, including mating rituals, warning calls, conveying location of food sources, and social learning.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In a number of species, males perform calls during mating rituals as a form of competition against other males and to signal to females.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Examples include frogs, hammer-headed bats, red deer, humpback whales, elephant seals, and songbirds.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Other instances of vocal communication include the alarm calls of the Campbell monkey, the territorial calls of gibbons, and the use of frequency in greater spear-nosed bats to distinguish between groups.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The vervet monkey gives a distinct alarm call for each of its four different predators, and the reactions of other monkeys vary appropriately according to the call.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, if an alarm call signals a python, the monkeys climb into the trees, whereas the "eagle" alarm causes monkeys to seek a hiding place on the ground.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Prairie dogs also use complex calls that signal predator differences.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] According to Con Slobodchikoff and others, prairie dog calls communicate the type, size, and speed of an approaching predator.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Whale vocalizations have been found to have different dialects based on social learning.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Mammalian acoustic culture was first discovered in southern resident orcas in 1978.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Not all animals use vocalization as a means of auditory communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Many arthropods rub specialized body parts together to produce sound.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Crickets and grasshoppers are well known for this, but many others use stridulation as well, including crustaceans, spiders, scorpions, wasps, ants, beetles, butterflies, moths, millipedes, and centipedes.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Another means of auditory communication is the vibration of swim bladders in bony fish.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The structure of swim bladders and the attached sonic muscles varies greatly across bony fish families, resulting in a wide variety of sounds.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Striking body parts together can also produce auditory signals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] A well-known example of this is the tail tip vibration of rattlesnakes as a warning signal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Other examples include bill clacking in birds, wing clapping in manakin courtship displays, and chest beating in gorillas.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Burrowing animal species are known to whistle to communicate threats, and sometimes mood.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Species such as the marmot species, including the groundhog (woodchuck), and the alpine marmot show this trait.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Whistling is used by animals such as prairie dogs to communicate threats, with prairie dogs having one of the most complex communication systems in the animal kingdom.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Prairie dogs are able to communicate an animal's speed, shape, size, species, and for humans specific attire and if the human is carrying a gun.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This method of communication is usually done by having a sentry stand on two feet and surveying for potential threats while the rest of the pack finds food.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Once a threat has been identified the sentry sounds a whistle alarm, (sometimes describing the threat) at which point the pack retreats to their burrows.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The intensity of the threat is usually determined by how long the sentry whistles.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The sentry continues to whistle the alarm until the entirety of the pack has gone to safety, at which point the sentry returns to the burrow.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Despite being the oldest method of communication, chemical communication is one of the least understood forms due in part to the sheer abundance of chemicals in our environment and the difficulty of detecting and measuring all the chemicals in a sample.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The ability to detect chemicals in the environment serves many functions, a crucial one being the detection of food, a function that first arose in single-celled organisms (bacteria) living in the oceans during the early days of life on Earth.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] As this function evolved, organisms began to differentiate between chemical compounds emanating from resources, conspecifics (same species; i.e., mates and kin), and heterospecifics (different species; i.e., competitors and predators).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For instance, a small minnow species may do well to avoid habitat with a detectable concentration of chemical cues associated with a predator species such as a northern pike.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Minnows with the ability to perceive the presence of predators before they are close enough to be seen and then respond with adaptive behavior (such as hiding) are more likely to survive and reproduce.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Atlantic salmon go a step further than detecting a predator's cue: when an individual is damaged by a predator, it releases a chemical cue to its conspecifics.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] As has also been observed in other species, acidification and changes in pH physically disrupt these chemical cues, which has various implications for animal behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Scent marking and scent rubbing are common forms of olfactory communication in mammals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] An example of scent rubbing by an animal can be seen from bears, bears do this as a way to mark territory or let others know they are there and to stay away.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Wolves scent-mark frequently during the breeding season.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Electrocommunication is a rare form of communication in animals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It is seen primarily in aquatic animals, though some land mammals, notably the platypus and echidnas, sense electric fields that might be used for communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Weakly electric fishes provide an example of electrocommunication, together with electrolocation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] These fish use an electric organ to generate an electric field, which is detected by electroreceptors.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Differences in the waveform and frequency of changes in the field convey information on species, sex, and identity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] These electric signals can be generated in response to hormones, circadian rhythms, and interactions with other fish.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] They can also serve to mediate social hierarchy amongst species that have a social order.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some predators, such as sharks and rays, are able to eavesdrop on these electrogenic fish through passive electroreception.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Touch is a key factor in many social interactions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In a fight, touch may be used to challenge an opponent and to coordinate movements during the fight.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It may also be used by the loser to indicate submission.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Mammals often initiate mating by grooming, stroking or rubbing against each other.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This provides the opportunity to apply chemical signals and to assess those excreted by the potential mate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Touch may also announce the intention of the male to mount the female, as when a male kangaroo grabs the tail of a female.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] During mating, touch stimuli are important for pair positioning, coordination and genital stimulation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Touch is widely used for social integration, a use that is typified by the social grooming of one animal by another.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] cues on the groomed individual, perhaps adding additional ones.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This behaviour has been observed in social insects, birds and mammals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some ant species recruit fellow workers to new food finds by first tapping them with their antennae and forelegs, then leading them to the food source while keeping physical contact.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] "Patrollers" leave the nest to check for danger nearby and return to recruit "foragers" by making physical contact.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Huddling promotes heat exchange, together with the transfer of olfactory or tactile information.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some organisms live in constant contact in a colony, for example colonial corals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] When individuals are linked tightly in this way an entire colony can react on the aversive or alarm movements made by only a few individuals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In several herbivorous insect nymphs and larvae, aggregations where there is prolonged contact play a major role in group coordination.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] These aggregations may take the form of a procession or a rosette.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Seismic communication is the exchange of information using self-generated vibrational signals transmitted via a substrate such as the soil, water, spider webs, plant stems, or a blade of grass.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This form of communication has several advantages, for example it can be sent regardless of light and noise levels, and it usually has a short range and short persistence, which may reduce the danger of detection by predators.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The use of seismic communication is found in many taxa, including frogs, kangaroo rats, mole rats, bees, nematode worms, and others.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Tetrapods usually make seismic waves by drumming on the ground with a body part, a signal that is sensed by the sacculus of the receiver.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The sacculus is an organ in the inner ear containing a membranous sac that is used for balance, but can also detect seismic waves in animals that use this form of communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Vibrations may be combined with other sorts of communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Several snakes have the ability to sense infrared thermal radiation, which allows these reptiles to derive thermal images from the radiant heat emitted by predators or prey at wavelengths between 5 and 30 μm.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The accuracy of this sense is such that a blind rattlesnake can target its strike to the vulnerable body parts of a prey animal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It was previously thought that the pit organs evolved primarily as prey detectors, but it is now believed that they may also be used to control body temperature.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The facial pits enabling thermoregulation underwent parallel evolution in pitvipers and some boas and pythons, having evolved once in pitvipers and multiple times in boas and pythons.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The electrophysiology of the structure is similar between lineages, but it differs in gross structure anatomy.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Most superficially, pitvipers possess one large pit organ on either side of the head, between the eye and the nostril (loreal pit), while boas and pythons have three or more comparatively smaller pits lining the upper and sometimes the lower lip, in or between the scales.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Those of the pitvipers are the more advanced, having a suspended sensory membrane as opposed to a simple pit structure.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Within the family Viperidae, the pit organ is seen only in the subfamily Crotalinae: the pitvipers.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Despite the detection of IR radiation, the pits' IR mechanism is dissimilar to photoreceptors; while photoreceptors detect light via photochemical reactions, the protein in the facial pits of snakes is a temperature sensitive ion channel.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It senses infrared signals through a mechanism involving warming of the pit organ, rather than chemical reaction to light.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This is consistent with the thin pit membrane, which allows incoming IR radiation to quickly and precisely warm a given ion channel and trigger a nerve impulse, as well as vascularize the pit membrane to rapidly cool the ion channel back to its original "resting" or "inactive" temperature.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Common vampire bats (*Desmodus rotundus*) have specialized IR sensors in their nose-leaf.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Vampire bats are the only mammals that feed exclusively on blood.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The IR sense enables Desmodus to localize homeothermic animals such as cattle and horses within a range of about 10 to 15 cm.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This infrared perception may be used in detecting regions of maximal blood flow on targeted prey.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Autocommunication is a type of communication in which the sender and receiver are the same individual.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The sender emits a signal that is altered by the environment and eventually is received by the same individual.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The altered signal provides information that can indicate food, predators or conspecifics.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Because the sender and receiver are the same animal, selection pressure maximizes signal efficacy, i.e. the degree to which an emitted signal is correctly identified by a receiver despite propagation distortion and noise.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There are some species, such as the pacific herring, which have evolved to intercept these messages from their predators.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] They are able to use it as an early warning sign and respond defensively.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There are two types of autocommunication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The first is active electrolocation, where the organism emits an electrical pulse through its electric organ and senses the projected geometrical property of the object.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This is found in the electric fishes, the Gymnotiformes (knifefishes) and the Mormyridae (elephantfishes).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The second type of autocommunication is echolocation, found in bats and toothed whales.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Echolocation involves emitting sounds and interpreting the vibrations that return from objects.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In bats, echolocation also serves the purpose of mapping their environment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] They are capable of recognizing a space they have been in before without any visible light because they can memorize patterns in the feedback they get from echolocation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There are many functions of animal communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] However, some have been studied in more detail than others.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Animal communication plays a vital role in determining the winner of contest over a resource.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Many species have distinct signals that signal aggression or willingness to attack or signals to convey retreat during competitions over food, territories, or mates.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Animals produce signals to attract the attention of a possible mate or to solidify pair bonds.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] These signals frequently involve the display of body parts or postures.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, a gazelle will assume characteristic poses to initiate mating.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] often have symmetrical displays that they make to each other.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] in mammals can indicate a female's breeding status or attract other mates.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Signals used to claim or defend a territory, food, or a mate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] ) will show greater signs of aggression from farther distances between males than between females when defending a territory or mate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It is believed that males have evolved to remain distant from each other due to higher reproductive consequences as opposed to females.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some animals who are fearful of stimuli will attack anyone near them.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Many animals make "food calls" to attract a mate, offspring, or other members of a social group to a food source.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Young ravens will signal to older ravens when they encounter new or untested food.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] will send food calls to inform other monkeys of a food source to avoid punishment.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] are released by many social insects to lead the other members of the society to the food source.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] leave a pheromone trail on the ground that can be followed by other ants to lead them to the food source.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Alarm calls communicate the threat of a predator.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This allows all members of a social group (and sometimes other species) to respond accordingly.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This may include running for cover, becoming immobile, or gathering into a group to reduce the risk of attack.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Alarm signals are not always vocalizations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Crushed ants will release an alarm pheromone to attract more ants and send them into an attack state.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Signals that will modify the meaning of subsequent signals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] which signals that a subsequent aggressive signal is part of a play fight rather than a serious aggressive episode.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Animal signals are often easier to describe than to interpret.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It is tempting, especially with domesticated animals and apes, to anthropomorphize, that is, to interpret animal actions in human terms, but this can be quite misleading; for example, an ape's "smile" is often a sign of aggression.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Also, the same gesture may have different meanings depending on context within which it occurs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, a domestic dog's tail wag and posture may be used in different ways to convey many meanings as illustrated in Charles Darwin's The Expression of the Emotions in Man and Animals published in 1872.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some of Darwin's illustrations are reproduced here.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Much animal communication is intraspecific, that is, it occurs between members of the same species.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] As for interspecific communication, that between predator and prey is of particular interest.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] If a prey animal moves, makes a noise or vibrations, or emits a smell in such a way that a predator can detect it, it is unwittingly communicating with its predator.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This type of communication is known as interceptive eavesdropping if a predator intercepts a message intended for conspecifics.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There are however, some actions of prey species are clearly directed to actual or potential predators.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] A good example is warning coloration: species such as wasps that are capable of harming potential predators are often brightly coloured, and this modifies the behavior of the predator, who either instinctively or as the result of experience will avoid attacking such an animal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some forms of mimicry fall in the same category: for example hoverflies are coloured in the same way as wasps, and although they are unable to sting, the strong avoidance of wasps by predators gives the hoverfly some protection.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There are also behavioural changes that act in a similar way to warning colouration.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, canines such as wolves and coyotes may adopt an aggressive posture, such as growling with their teeth bared, to indicate they will fight if necessary, and rattlesnakes use their well-known rattle to warn potential predators of their venomous bite.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Sometimes, a behavioural change and warning coloration will be combined, as in certain species of amphibians which have most of their body coloured to blend with their surroundings, except for a brightly coloured belly.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] When confronted with a potential threat, they show their belly, indicating that they are poisonous in some way.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Another example of prey to predator communication is the pursuit-deterrent signal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Pursuit-deterrent signals occur when prey indicates to a predator that pursuit would be unprofitable because the signaler is prepared to escape.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Pursuit-deterrent signals provide a benefit to both the signaler and receiver; they prevent the sender from wasting time and energy fleeing, and they prevent the receiver from investing in a costly pursuit that is unlikely to result in capture.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Such signals can advertise prey's ability to escape, and reflect phenotypic condition (quality advertisement), or can advertise that the prey has detected the predator (perception advertisement).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Pursuit-deterrent signals have been reported for a wide variety of taxa, including fish (Godin and Davis, 1995), lizards (Cooper etc. al., 2004), ungulates (Caro, 1995), rabbits (Holley 1993), primates (Zuberbuhler et al.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] A familiar example of quality advertisement pursuit-deterrent signal is *stotting* (sometimes called *pronking*), a pronounced combination of stiff-legged running while simultaneously jumping shown by some antelopes such as Thomson's gazelle in the presence of a predator.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] At least 11 hypotheses for stotting have been proposed.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] A leading theory today is that it alerts predators that the element of surprise has been lost.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Predators like cheetahs rely on surprise attacks, proven by the fact that chases are rarely successful when antelope stot.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Predators do not waste energy on a chase that will likely be unsuccessful (optimal foraging behavior).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Quality advertisement can be communicated by modes other than visual.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The banner-tailed kangaroo rat produces several complex foot-drumming patterns in a number of different contexts, one of which is when it encounters a snake.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The foot-drumming may alert nearby offspring but most likely conveys vibrations through the ground that the rat is too alert for a successful attack, thus preventing the snake's predatory pursuit.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Typically, predators attempt to reduce communication to prey as this will generally reduce the effectiveness of their hunting.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] However, some forms of predator to prey communication occur in ways that change the behavior of the prey and make their capture easier, i.e. deception by the predator.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] A well-known example is the angler fish, an ambush predator which waits for its prey to come to it.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It has a fleshy bioluminescent growth protruding from its forehead which it dangles in front of its jaws.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Smaller fish attempt to take the lure, placing themselves in a better position for the angler fish to catch them.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Another example of deceptive communication is observed in the genus of jumping spiders (*Myrmarachne*).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] These spiders are commonly referred to as "antmimicking spiders" because of the way they wave their front legs in the air to simulate antennae.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Various ways in which humans interpret the behavior of animals, or give commands to them, are consistent with the definition of interspecies communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Skillful interpretation of animal communications may be critical to the welfare of animals that are being cared for or trained by humans.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Non-human animal species may interpret the signals of humans differently than humans themselves.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For instance, a pointing command refers to a location rather than an object in dogs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The importance of communication is evident from the highly elaborate morphology, behaviour and physiology that some animals have evolved to facilitate this.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] These include some of the most striking structures in the animal kingdom, such as the peacock's tail, the antlers of a stag and the frill of the frill-necked lizard, but also include even the modest red spot on a European herring gull's bill.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Highly elaborate behaviours have evolved for communication such as the dancing of cranes, the pattern changes of cuttlefish, and the gathering and arranging of materials by bowerbirds.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Other evidence for the importance of communication in animals is the prioritisation of physiological features to this function.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, birdsong appears to have brain structures entirely devoted to its production.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] All these adaptations require evolutionary explanation.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Significant contributions to the first of these problems were made by Konrad Lorenz and other early ethologists.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] By comparing related species within groups, they showed that movements and body parts that in the primitive forms had no communicative function could be "captured" in a context where communication would be functional for one or both partners, and could evolve into a more elaborate, specialised form.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, Desmond Morris showed in a study of grass finches that a beak-wiping response occurred in a range of species, serving a preening function, but that in some species this had been elaborated into a courtship signal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The second problem has been more controversial.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The early ethologists assumed that communication occurred for the good of the species as a whole, but this would require a process of group selection which is believed to be mathematically impossible in the evolution of sexually reproducing animals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Altruism towards an unrelated group is not widely accepted in the scientific community, but rather can be seen as reciprocal altruism, expecting the same behaviour from others, a benefit of living in a group.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Sociobiologists argued that behaviours that benefited a whole group of animals might emerge as a result of selection pressures acting solely on the individual.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In the case of communication, an important discussion by John Krebs and Richard Dawkins established hypotheses for the evolution of such apparently altruistic or mutualistic communications as alarm calls and courtship signals to emerge under individual selection.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This led to the realization that communication might not always be "honest" (indeed, there are some obvious examples where it is not, as in mimicry).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The possibility of evolutionarily stable dishonest communication has been the subject of much controversy, with Amotz Zahavi in particular arguing that it cannot exist in the long term.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] One theory to explain the evolution of traits like a peacock's tail is 'runaway selection'.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This requires two traits—a trait that exists, like the bright tail, and a preexisting bias in the female to select for that trait.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Females prefer the more elaborate tails, and thus those males are able to mate successfully.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Exploiting the psychology of the female, a positive feedback loop is enacted and the tail becomes bigger and brighter.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Eventually, the evolution will level off because the survival costs to the male do not allow for the trait to be elaborated any further.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Two theories exist to explain runaway selection.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This theory states that an elaborate display is an honest signal of fitness and truly is a better mate.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This explains that the peacock's tail is a handicap, requiring energy to keep and makes it more visible to predators.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Thus, the signal is costly to maintain, and remains an honest indicator of the signaler's condition.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Another assumption is that the signal is more costly for low quality males to produce than for higher quality males to produce.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This is simply because the higher quality males have more energy reserves available to allocate to costly signaling.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Ethologists and sociobiologists have characteristically analysed animal communication in terms of more or less automatic responses to stimuli, without raising the question of whether the animals concerned understand the meaning of the signals they emit and receive.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] That is a key question in animal cognition.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There are some signalling systems that seem to demand a more advanced understanding.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] A much discussed example is the use of alarm calls by vervet monkeys.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Metacommunication, discussed above, also seems to require a more sophisticated cognitive process.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The same researchers later found that common bottlenose dolphin (*Tursiops truncatus*) mothers inflect their signature whistle when their dependent calf is present.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Signature whistles, which are in a higher frequency range than humans can hear, have an important role in facilitating mother–calf contact.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In the Sarasota Dolphin Research Program's library of recordings were 19 female common bottlenose dolphins producing signature whistles both with and without the presence of their calf.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In all 19 cases, the mother dolphin inflected the signature whistle when their calf was present, by reaching a higher frequency, or using a wider frequency range.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Similarly, humans use higher fundamental frequencies and a wider pitch range to inflect child–directed speech (CDS).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This has rarely been discovered in other species.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] The researchers stated that CDS benefits for humans are cueing the child to pay attention, long-term bonding, and promoting the development of lifelong vocal learning, with parallels in these bottlenose dolphins in an example of convergent evolution.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Other species which can transmit identity information using name-like calls include marmosets and elephants.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Another controversial issue is the extent to which human behaviours resemble animal communication, or whether all such communication has disappeared as a result of our linguistic capacity.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Some of our bodily features—eyebrows, beards and moustaches, deep adult male voices, perhaps female breasts—strongly resemble adaptations to producing signals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Ethologists such as Irenäus Eibl-Eibesfeldt have argued that facial gestures such as smiling, grimacing, and the eyebrow flash on greeting are universal human communicative signals that can be related to corresponding signals in other primates.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Given how recently spoken language has emerged, it is very likely that human body language does include some more or less involuntary responses that have a similar origin to the communication we have.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Humans also often seek to mimic animals' communicative signals in order to interact with them.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] For example, cats have a mild affiliative response of slowly closing their eyes; humans often mimic this signal towards a pet cat to establish a tolerant relationship.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Stroking, petting and rubbing pet animals are all actions that probably work through their natural patterns of interspecific communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Dogs have an ability to understand human communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In object choice tasks, dogs utilize human communicative gestures such as pointing and direction of gaze in order to locate hidden food and toys.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] However, in contrast to humans pointing has a different meaning for dogs as it refers to a direction or location.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It has also been shown that dogs exhibit a left gaze bias when looking at human faces, indicating that they are capable of reading human emotions.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Dogs do not make use of direction of gaze or exhibit left gaze bias with other dogs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In general, animal utterances are responses to external stimuli, and do not refer to matters removed in time and space.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Matters of relevance at a distance, such as distant food sources, tend to be indicated to other individuals by body language instead, for example wolf activity before a hunt, or the information conveyed in honeybee dance language.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It is therefore unclear to what extent utterances are automatic responses and to what extent deliberate intent plays a part.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In contrast to human language, animal communication systems are usually not able to express conceptual generalizations.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] (Cetaceans and some primates may be notable exceptions).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] Human languages combine elements to produce new messages (a property known as **creativity**).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] One factor in this is that much human language growth is based upon conceptual ideas and hypothetical structures, both being far greater capabilities in humans than animals.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] This appears far less common in animal communication systems, although current research into animal culture is still an ongoing process with many new discoveries.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] In 2009 it was reported that affixation may play a role in the call meanings of Campbell's mona monkey.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] There is a possibility for error within communication between animals, such as when there is a large distance between the two communicating subjects, or if the signal that is being communicated to the "listener" is complex.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/animal-communication] It may not always be clear to the "listener" where the location of the communication is coming from, as the "singer" can sometimes deceive them and create more error.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell had at least as much impact on the study of language and social interaction generally as just nonverbal communication because he was interested in the study of communication more broadly than is often recognized.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell understood body movements to be culturally patterned rather than universal.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] His students were required to read widely, sources not only in communication but also anthropology and linguistics.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] "Birdwhistell himself was deeply disappointed that his general communicative interests and goals were not appropriately understood." Collaborations with others, including initially Margaret Mead and Gregory Bateson, and later, Erving Goffman and Dell Hymes had huge influence on his work.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell was born in Cincinnati on September 29, 1918, and died October 19, 1994.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] He was raised and went to school in Ohio.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] He graduated from Fostoria High School in 1936, and was involved in the history club, debate team, journalism, and school plays.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell received his BA in sociology in 1940 from Miami University, his MA in anthropology in 1941 from Ohio State University, and his PhD in anthropology in 1951 from the University of Chicago, where he studied with Lloyd Warner and Fred Eggan.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] From 1944 to 1946 he conducted dissertation fieldwork among the Kutenai Indians of British Columbia during which he first realized that tribal members moved differently depending on whether they were speaking English or Kutenai, which sparked his interest in nonverbal behavior.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] While completing his dissertation, he taught at the University of Toronto (Ontario), where Erving Goffman was one of his students.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] From 1944 to 1946 he was lecturer in anthropology at the University of Toronto, working with G.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Carpenter, who were in the same department.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] In 1946 he went to Kentucky and took a position at the University of Louisville, where he taught for 10 years, and helped in racial integration of the university.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] While there he established the Interdisciplinary Committee on Culture and Communication, and organized a series of annual seminars on Culture and Communication, resulting in the publication of *Explorations in Communication*.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] In addition to Edmund Snow Carpenter, Marshall McLuhan, and Birdwhistell, Lawrence K.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Through the 1950s he participated in multiple interdisciplinary collaborations: at the Foreign Service Institute of the United States Department of State, where he first outlined his ideas about the study of nonverbal behavior, working with Edward T.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Hockett; at the Macy Conferences on Group Processes, with Gregory Bateson, Margaret Mead, and many others; and at the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences, where he participated in the *Natural History of an Interview* project with Gregory Bateson, Frieda Fromm-Reichmann, Norman A.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell taught at the State University of New York at Buffalo from 1956 to 1959.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] In 1959 he was appointed senior research scientist at the Eastern Pennsylvania Psychiatric Institute, and simultaneously Professor of Research in Anthropology at Temple University in Philadelphia.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] At EPPI he managed a lab that included a fully equipped 16mm film studio, a resident cinematographer (Jacques van Vlack), an artist who illustrated research findings, and numerous graduate students and visitors who conferred with him and his colleague, psychiatrist Albert E.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell argued strongly for the use of film as an essential tool in the study of nonverbal behavior as a way to permit "observation and analysis of human social behavior which has hitherto been hidden from comparative analysis".
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Together with Jacques van Vlack (the filmmaker), he prepared a series of films that were commercially available, although, as with his teaching, they were intended mostly for a technically trained audience.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] *TDR- 009*, an eighty-minute 16 mm black-and-white sound film of an English pub scene in a middle class London hotel.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell and van Vlack observed behavior of listeners in relationship to speakers during the film.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell at the Second Linguistic-Kinesic Conference Nov.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] 4–7, 1964*, is simply a documentary record of two lectures Birdwhistell presented to a seminar group assembled for a few days to learn from his research team at EPPI in 1964.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Seminar participants were primarily senior research scientists, including linguists, psychiatrists, anthropologists, and psychologists; McQuown and Scheflen, working with Birdwhistell on the *Natural History of an Interview* project, were among the participants.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Much of the work at EPPI was a continuation of the *Natural History of an Interview* project, working mostly with Scheflen, while Brosin continued different parts of the same project from the Western Psychiatric Institute & Clinic in Pennsylvania with Adam Kendon, William S.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Condon, Kai Erikson, Harvey Sarles, and occasional visits from Bateson.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] The two teams kept in touch, meeting several days per month between 1960 and 1964 to complete their analysis.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] A third team, under McQuown's direction at the University of Chicago, included Starkey Duncan Jr., William M.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Austin, Raven McDavid Jr., and William Offenkrantz.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] The Chicago team focused on paralanguage (non-lexical aspects of voice, including intonation), while the Pennsylvania teams attended to kinesics (body motion communication).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] The final report was completed in 1968, but proved unpublishable due to its length (5 volumes), and the complexity of the transcriptions (taking up 3 of the 5 volumes), so it was circulated via the microfilm series of the University of Chicago.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] It was commonly understood that "no serious doctoral student at the University of Pennsylvania who was interested in culture and human conduct" could avoid his courses.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell reputedly came to the attention of Margaret Mead and Gregory Bateson when he attended a showing of one of their ethnographic films (they were pioneers of the use of film as an ethnographic tool).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Both Mead and Bateson became lifelong supporters and influences.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] He was also influenced by David Efron's earlier work, the first major study of the influence of culture on gesture prepared under Franz Boas, noted American anthropologist, and Eliot D.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell died of liver cancer on October 19, 1994, at his home in Brigantine, New Jersey.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Some of the major early books discussing nonverbal communication that owe a substantial debt to Birdwhistell and his research were Sebeok, Hayes and Bateson (1964), Davis (1973), Scheflen (1973), Kendon, Harris and Key (1975), Kendon (1977), Sarles (1977), Wolfgang (1979), and Davis (1982).
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Goffman became one of the best-known sociologists with an international reputation, and nearly all of his publications became best sellers.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell influenced Lomax's development of cantometrics and choreometrics.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Byers was quite important in the study of visual communication.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Winkin went on to develop the anthropology of communication in Europe.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Many of Birdwhistell's publications were short pieces, gathered together to make up *Kinesics and Context*.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Birdwhistell viewed communication as a continuous, multichannel (today, the more common term is multimodal) process through which and in which social interaction occurs.
[src:ray-birdwhistell/ray-birdwhistell] Although he is best known for inventing kinesics, his influence was much larger: he helped establish the logical underpinnings of language and social interaction research generally, and such approaches as the coordinated management of meaning.
